# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Causes may include sepsis, pancreatitis, trauma, pneumonia, and aspiration.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The underlying mechanism involves diffuse injury to cells which form the barrier of the microscopic air sacs of the lungs, surfactant dysfunction, activation of the immune system, and dysfunction of the body's regulation of blood clotting.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] In effect, ARDS impairs the lungs' ability to exchange oxygen and carbon dioxide.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Adult diagnosis is based on a PaO2/FiO2 ratio (ratio of partial pressure arterial oxygen and fraction of inspired oxygen) of less than 300 mm Hg despite a positive end-expiratory pressure (PEEP) of more than 5 cm H2O.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Cardiogenic pulmonary edema, as the cause, must be excluded.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Environmental exposures have been associated with an increased susceptibility to acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Chronic exposure to ambient air pollution, such as fine particulate matter (PM2.5) and ozone, have been linked to higher risks of developing ARDS following acute events such as sepsis or trauma.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The exposures are thought to contribute to baseline pulmonary inflammation and endothelial dysfunction, potentially amplifying the response to subsequent lung injury.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Some studies have also reported associations between higher ambient ozone levels and increased mortality among patients with ARDS.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The primary treatment involves mechanical ventilation together with treatments directed at the underlying cause.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Ventilation strategies include using low volumes and low pressures.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] If oxygenation remains insufficient, lung recruitment maneuvers and neuromuscular blockers may be used.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] If these are insufficient, extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO) may be an option.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The syndrome is associated with a death rate between 35 and 46%.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Globally, ARDS affects more than 3 million people a year.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The condition was first described in 1967.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] There are separate diagnostic criteria for children and those in areas of the world with fewer resources.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Environmental and geographic factors may also contribute to variation in ARDS incidence and outcomes, as populations with higher exposure to air pollution have demonstrated increased susceptibility and worse clinical outcomes.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] ARDS accounts for approximately 10% of intensive care unit (ICU) admissions and up to 23% of patients requiring mechanical ventilation, with mortality rates ranging from 30% to 45% depending on severity and comorbid conditions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The signs and symptoms of ARDS often begin within two hours of an inciting event, but have been known to take as long as 1–3 days; diagnostic criteria require a known insult to have happened within 7 days of the syndrome.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Signs and symptoms may include shortness of breath, fast breathing, and a low oxygen level in the blood due to abnormal ventilation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Other common symptoms include muscle fatigue and general weakness, low blood pressure, a dry, hacking cough, and fever.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] There are *direct* and *indirect* causes of ARDS depending whether the lungs are initially affected.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Direct causes include pneumonia (including bacterial and viral), aspiration, inhalational lung injury, lung contusion, chest trauma, and near-drowning.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Indirect causes include sepsis, shock, pancreatitis, trauma (e.g. fat embolism), cardiopulmonary bypass, TRALI, burns, increased intracranial pressure.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Fewer cases of ARDS are linked to large volumes of fluid used during post-trauma resuscitation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] ARDS is a form of fluid accumulation in the lungs not explained by heart failure (noncardiogenic pulmonary edema).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] It is typically provoked by an acute injury to the lungs that results in flooding of the lungs' microscopic air sacs responsible for the exchange of gases such as oxygen and carbon dioxide with capillaries in the lungs.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Additional common findings in ARDS include partial collapse of the alveoli (atelectasis) and low levels of oxygen in the blood (hypoxemia).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The clinical syndrome is associated with pathological findings including pneumonia, eosinophilic pneumonia, cryptogenic organizing pneumonia, acute fibrinous organizing pneumonia, and diffuse alveolar damage (DAD).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Of these, the pathology most commonly associated with ARDS is DAD, which is characterized by a diffuse inflammation of lung tissue.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The triggering insult to the tissue usually results in an initial release of chemical signals and other inflammatory mediators secreted by local epithelial and endothelial cells.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Neutrophils and some T-lymphocytes quickly migrate into the inflamed lung tissue and contribute in the amplification of the phenomenon.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The typical histological presentation involves diffuse alveolar damage and hyaline membrane formation in alveolar walls.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Although the triggering mechanisms are not completely understood, recent research has examined the role of inflammation and mechanical stress.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] One research group has reported that broncho-alveolar lavage fluid in later-stage ARDS often contains trichomonads, in an amoeboid form (i.e. lacking their characteristic flagellum) which makes them difficult to identify under the microscope.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] There is growing awareness that ARDS is not a single disease, but consists of sub-phenotypes which likely have distinct underlying mechanisms.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] However sub-phenotyping using the blood may not reflect changes in the alveolar space, with implications for future stratified medicine trials.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Diagnostic criteria for ARDS have changed over time as understanding of the pathophysiology has evolved.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The international consensus criteria for ARDS were most recently updated in 2012 and are known as the "Berlin definition".
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] In addition to generally broadening the diagnostic thresholds, other notable changes from the prior 1994 consensus criteria include discouraging the term "acute lung injury", and defining grades of ARDS severity according to degree of decrease in the oxygen content of the blood.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The 2012 "Berlin criteria" are a modification of the prior 1994 consensus conference definitions (see *history*).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Radiologic imaging has long been a criterion for diagnosis of ARDS.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Original definitions of ARDS specified that correlative chest X-ray findings were required for diagnosis, the diagnostic criteria have been expanded over time to accept CT and ultrasound findings as equally contributory.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Generally, radiographic findings of fluid accumulation (pulmonary edema) affecting both lungs and unrelated to increased cardiopulmonary vascular pressure (such as in heart failure) may be suggestive of ARDS.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Acute respiratory distress syndrome is usually treated with mechanical ventilation in the intensive care unit (ICU).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Mechanical ventilation is usually delivered through a rigid tube which enters the oral cavity and is secured in the airway (endotracheal intubation), or by tracheostomy when prolonged ventilation (≥2 weeks) is necessary.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The role of non-invasive ventilation is limited to the very early period of the disease or to prevent worsening respiratory distress in individuals with atypical pneumonias, lung bruising, or major surgery patients, who are at risk of developing ARDS.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Treatment of the underlying cause is crucial.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Appropriate antibiotic therapy is started as soon as culture results are available, or if infection is suspected (whichever is earlier).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Empirical therapy may be appropriate if local microbiological surveillance is efficient.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Where possible the origin of the infection is removed.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] When sepsis is diagnosed, appropriate local protocols are followed.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The overall goal of mechanical ventilation is to maintain acceptable gas exchange to meet the body's metabolic demands and to minimize adverse effects in its application.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The parameters PEEP (positive end-expiratory pressure, to keep alveoli open), mean airway pressure (to promote recruitment (opening) of easily collapsible alveoli and predictor of hemodynamic effects), and plateau pressure (best predictor of alveolar overdistention) are used.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Previously, mechanical ventilation aimed to achieve tidal volumes (*V*t) of 12–15 ml/kg (where the weight is ideal body weight rather than actual weight).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Recent studies have shown that high tidal volumes can overstretch alveoli resulting in volutrauma (secondary lung injury).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The ARDS Clinical Network, or ARDSNet, completed a clinical trial that showed improved mortality when people with ARDS were ventilated with a tidal volume of 6 ml/kg compared to the traditional 12 ml/kg.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Low tidal volumes (*V*t) may cause a permitted rise in blood carbon dioxide levels and collapse of alveoli because of their inherent tendency to increase shunting within the lung.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Physiologic dead space cannot change as it is ventilation without perfusion.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] A shunt is a perfusion without ventilation within a lung region.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Low tidal volume ventilation was the primary independent variable associated with reduced mortality in the NIH-sponsored ARDSNet trial of tidal volume in ARDS.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] No particular ventilator mode is known to improve mortality in acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Some practitioners favor airway pressure release ventilation when treating ARDS.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] A patient with ARDS, on average, spends between 8 and 11 days on a mechanical ventilator; APRV may reduce this time significantly and thus may conserve valuable resources.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Positive end-expiratory pressure (PEEP) is used in mechanically ventilated people with ARDS to improve oxygenation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] In ARDS, three populations of alveoli can be distinguished.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The recruitable alveoli represent a continuous population, some of which can be recruited with minimal PEEP, and others can only be recruited with high levels of PEEP.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] An additional complication is that some alveoli can only be opened with higher airway pressures than are needed to keep them open, hence the justification for maneuvers where PEEP is increased to very high levels for seconds to minutes before dropping the PEEP to a lower level.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] PEEP can be harmful; high PEEP necessarily increases mean airway pressure and alveolar pressure, which can damage normal alveoli by overdistension resulting in DAD.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] A compromise between the beneficial and adverse effects of PEEP is inevitable.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The 'best PEEP' used to be defined as 'some' cmH 2O above the lower inflection point (LIP) in the sigmoidal pressure-volume relationship curve of the lung.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Recent research has shown that the LIP-point pressure is no better than any pressure above it, as recruitment of collapsed alveoli—and, more importantly, the overdistension of aerated units—occur throughout the whole inflation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Despite the awkwardness of most procedures used to trace the pressure-volume curve, it is still used by some to define the *minimum* PEEP to be applied to their patients.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Some new ventilators can automatically plot a pressure-volume curve.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Some authors suggest performing a 'recruiting maneuver'—a short time at a very high continuous positive airway pressure, such as 50 cmH 2O (4.9 kPa)—to recruit or open collapsed units with a high distending pressure before restoring previous ventilation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The final PEEP level should be the one just before the drop in PaO 2 or peripheral blood oxygen saturation during a step-down trial.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] A large randomized controlled trial of patients with ARDS found that lung recruitment maneuvers and PEEP titration was associated with high rates of barotrauma and pneumothorax and increased mortality.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Intrinsic PEEP (iPEEP) or auto-PEEP—first described by John Marini of St.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Paul Regions Hospital—is a potentially unrecognized contributor to PEEP in intubated individuals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Its measurement is recommended in the treatment of people who have ARDS, especially when using high-frequency (oscillatory/jet) ventilation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The position of lung infiltrates in acute respiratory distress syndrome is non-uniform.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Repositioning into the prone position (face down) might improve oxygenation by relieving atelectasis and improving perfusion.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] If this is done early in the treatment of severe ARDS, it confers a mortality benefit of 26% compared to supine ventilation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] However, attention should be paid to avoid the SIDS in the management of the respiratory distressed infants by continuous careful monitoring of their cardiovascular system.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Several studies have shown that pulmonary function and outcome are better in people with ARDS who lost weight or whose pulmonary wedge pressure was lowered by diuresis or fluid restriction.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] As of 2019, it is uncertain whether or not treatment with corticosteroids improves overall survival.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Corticosteroids may increase the number of ventilator-free days during the first 28 days of hospitalization.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] One study found that dexamethasone may help.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The combination of hydrocortisone, ascorbic acid, and thiamine also requires further study as of 2018.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Inhaled nitric oxide (NO) selectively widens the lung's arteries which allows for more blood flow to open alveoli for gas exchange.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Despite evidence of increased oxygenation status, there is no evidence that inhaled nitric oxide decreases morbidity and mortality in people with ARDS.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Furthermore, nitric oxide may cause kidney damage and is not recommended as therapy for ARDS regardless of severity.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Alvelestat (AZD 9668) had been quoted according to one review article.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO) is mechanically applied prolonged cardiopulmonary support.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] There are two types of ECMO: Venovenous which provides respiratory support and venoarterial which provides respiratory and hemodynamic support.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] People with ARDS who do not require cardiac support typically undergo venovenous ECMO.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Multiple studies have shown the effectiveness of ECMO in acute respiratory failure.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Specifically, the CESAR (Conventional ventilatory support versus Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation for Severe Acute Respiratory failure) trial demonstrated that a group referred to an ECMO center demonstrated significantly increased survival compared to conventional management (63% to 47%).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] As of 2019, there is no evidence showing that treatments with exogenous surfactants, statins, beta-blockers or n-acetylcysteine decreases early mortality, late all-cause mortality, duration of mechanical ventilation, or number of ventilator-free days.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The overall prognosis of ARDS is poor, with mortality rates of approximately 40%.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Exercise limitation, physical and psychological sequelae, decreased physical quality of life, and increased costs and use of health care services are important sequelae of ARDS.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The annual rate of ARDS is generally 13–23 people per 100,000 in the general population.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] It is more common in people who are mechanically ventilated with acute lung injury (ALI) occurring in 16% of ventilated people.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Rates increased in 2020 due to COVID-19, with some cases also appearing similar to HAPE.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Worldwide, severe sepsis is the most common trigger causing ARDS.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] However, the majority of patients with all these conditions mentioned do not develop ARDS.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] It is unclear why some people with the mentioned factors above do not develop ARDS and others do.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Pneumonia and sepsis are the most common triggers, and pneumonia is present in up to 60% of patients and may be either causes or complications of ARDS.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Alcohol excess appears to increase the risk of ARDS.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Diabetes was originally thought to decrease the risk of ARDS, but this has shown to be due to an increase in the risk of pulmonary edema.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Elevated abdominal pressure of any cause is also probably a risk factor for the development of ARDS, particularly during mechanical ventilation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Acute respiratory distress syndrome was first described in 1967 by Ashbaugh *et al.* Initially there was no clearly established definition, which resulted in controversy regarding the incidence and death of ARDS.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] In 1988, an expanded definition was proposed, which quantified physiologic respiratory impairment.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] In 1994, a new definition was recommended by the American-European Consensus Conference Committee which recognized the variability in severity of pulmonary injury.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] If PaO 2:FiO 2 < 300 mmHg (40 kPa), then the definitions recommended a classification as "acute lung injury" (ALI).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Note that according to these criteria, arterial blood gas analysis and chest X-ray were required for formal diagnosis.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Limitations of these definitions include lack of precise definition of acuity, nonspecific imaging criteria, lack of precise definition of hypoxemia with regards to PEEP (affects arterial oxygen partial pressure), arbitrary PaO 2 thresholds without systematic data.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] In 2012, the Berlin Definition of ARDS was devised by the European Society of Intensive Care Medicine, and was endorsed by the American Thoracic Society and the Society of Critical Care Medicine.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] These recommendations were an effort to both update classification criteria in order to improve clinical usefulness and to clarify terminology.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Notably, the Berlin guidelines discourage the use of the term "acute lung injury" or ALI, as the term was commonly being misused to characterize a less severe degree of lung injury.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Instead, the committee proposes a classification of ARDS severity as mild, moderate, or severe according to arterial oxygen saturation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The Berlin definitions represent the current international consensus guidelines for both clinical and research classification of ARDS.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] ARDS is the severe form of acute lung injury (ALI), and of transfusion-related acute lung injury (TRALI), though there are other causes.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The Berlin definition included ALI as a mild form of ARDS.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] However, the criteria for the diagnosis of ARDS in the Berlin definition excludes many children, and a new definition for children was termed *pediatric* acute respiratory distress syndrome (PARDS); this is known as the PALICC definition (2015).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] There is ongoing research on the treatment of ARDS by interferon (IFN) beta-1a to aid in preventing leakage of vascular beds.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Traumakine (FP-1201-lyo) is a recombinant human IFN beta-1a drug, developed by the Finnish company Faron Pharmaceuticals, which is undergoing international phase-III clinical trials after an open-label, early-phase trial showed an 81% reduction-in-odds of 28-day mortality in ICU patients with ARDS.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] The drug is known to function by enhancing lung CD73 expression and increasing production of anti-inflammatory adenosine, such that vascular leaking and escalation of inflammation are reduced.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] Aspirin has been studied in those who are at high risk and was not found to be useful.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/acute-respiratory-distress-syndrome] An intravenous ascorbic acid treatment was tested in the 2019 RCT, in people with ARDS due to sepsis and there was no change in primary endpoints.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Like surface tension, adsorption is a consequence of surface energy.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] In a bulk material, all the bonding requirements (be they ionic, covalent, or metallic) of the constituent atoms of the material are fulfilled by other atoms in the material.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] However, atoms on the surface of the adsorbent are not wholly surrounded by other adsorbent atoms and therefore can attract adsorbates.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The exact nature of the bonding depends on the details of the species involved, but the adsorption process is generally classified as physisorption (characteristic of weak van der Waals forces) or chemisorption (characteristic of covalent bonding).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] It may also occur due to electrostatic attraction.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The nature of the adsorption can affect the structure of the adsorbed species.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] For example, polymer physisorption from solution can result in squashed structures on a surface.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Adsorption, ion exchange, and chromatography are sorption processes in which certain adsorbates are selectively transferred from the fluid phase to the surface of insoluble, rigid particles suspended in a vessel or packed in a column.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Pharmaceutical industry applications, which use adsorption as a means to prolong neurological exposure to specific drugs or parts thereof, are lesser known.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The word "adsorption" was coined in 1881 by German physicist Heinrich Kayser (1853–1940).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The adsorption of gases and solutes is usually described through isotherms, that is, the amount of adsorbate on the adsorbent as a function of its pressure (if gas) or concentration (for liquid phase solutes) at constant temperature.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The quantity adsorbed is nearly always normalized by the mass of the adsorbent to allow comparison of different materials.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] A number of different isotherm models have been developed.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] where x is the mass of adsorbate adsorbed, m is the mass of the adsorbent, P is the pressure of adsorbate (this can be changed to concentration if investigating solution rather than gas), and k and n are empirical constants for each adsorbent–adsorbate pair at a given temperature.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The function is not adequate at very high pressure because in reality $x/m$ has an asymptotic maximum as pressure increases without bound.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] As the temperature increases, the constants k and n change to reflect the empirical observation that the quantity adsorbed rises more slowly and higher pressures are required to saturate the surface.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Irving Langmuir was the first to derive a scientifically based adsorption isotherm in 1918.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The model applies to gases adsorbed on solid surfaces.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] It is a semi-empirical isotherm with a kinetic basis and was derived based on statistical thermodynamics.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] It is the most common isotherm equation to use due to its simplicity and its ability to fit a variety of adsorption data.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The surface is energetically homogeneous, and adsorbed molecules do not interact.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] At the maximum adsorption, only a monolayer is formed.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Adsorption only occurs on localized sites on the surface, not with other adsorbates.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] These four assumptions are seldom all true: there are always imperfections on the surface, adsorbed molecules are not necessarily inert, and the mechanism is clearly not the same for the first molecules to adsorb to a surface as for the last.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The fourth condition is the most troublesome, as frequently more molecules will adsorb to the monolayer; this problem is addressed by the BET isotherm for relatively flat (non-microporous) surfaces.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The Langmuir isotherm is nonetheless the first choice for most models of adsorption and has many applications in surface kinetics (usually called Langmuir–Hinshelwood kinetics) and thermodynamics.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Langmuir suggested that adsorption takes place through this mechanism: $A_{\text{g}}+S\rightleftharpoons AS$ , where *A* is a gas molecule, and *S* is an adsorption site.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The direct and inverse rate constants are *k* and *k*−1.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] where P is the partial pressure of the gas or the molar concentration of the solution.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] For very low pressures $\theta \approx KP$ , and for high pressures $\theta \approx 1$ .
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The value of $\theta$ is difficult to measure experimentally; usually, the adsorbate is a gas and the quantity adsorbed is given in moles, grams, or gas volumes at standard temperature and pressure (STP) per gram of adsorbent.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Through its slope and *y* intercept we can obtain *v*mon and *K*, which are constants for each adsorbent–adsorbate pair at a given temperature.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] *v*mon is related to the number of adsorption sites through the ideal gas law.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] If we assume that the number of sites is just the whole area of the solid divided into the cross section of the adsorbate molecules, we can easily calculate the surface area of the adsorbent.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The surface area of an adsorbent depends on its structure: the more pores it has, the greater the area, which has a big influence on reactions on surfaces.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] where *i* is each one of the gases that adsorb.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] 1) To choose between the Langmuir and Freundlich equations, the enthalpies of adsorption must be investigated.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] While the Langmuir model assumes that the energy of adsorption remains constant with surface occupancy, the Freundlich equation is derived with the assumption that the heat of adsorption continually decrease as the binding sites are occupied.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The choice of the model based on best fitting of the data is a common misconception.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] 2) The use of the linearized form of the Langmuir model is no longer common practice.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Advances in computational power allowed for nonlinear regression to be performed quickly and with higher confidence since no data transformation is required.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Often molecules do form multilayers, that is, some are adsorbed on already adsorbed molecules, and the Langmuir isotherm is not valid.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] In 1938 Stephen Brunauer, Paul Emmett, and Edward Teller developed a model isotherm that takes that possibility into account.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Their theory is called BET theory, after the initials in their last names.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The derivation of the formula is more complicated than Langmuir's (see links for complete derivation).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The key assumption used in deriving the BET equation that the successive heats of adsorption for all layers except the first are equal to the heat of condensation of the adsorbate.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The Langmuir isotherm is usually better for chemisorption, and the BET isotherm works better for physisorption for non-microporous surfaces.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] In other instances, molecular interactions between gas molecules previously adsorbed on a solid surface form significant interactions with gas molecules in the gaseous phases.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Hence, adsorption of gas molecules to the surface is more likely to occur around gas molecules that are already present on the solid surface, rendering the Langmuir adsorption isotherm ineffective for the purposes of modelling.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] This effect was studied in a system where nitrogen was the adsorbate and tungsten was the adsorbent by Paul Kisliuk (1922–2008) in 1957.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] To compensate for the increased probability of adsorption occurring around molecules present on the substrate surface, Kisliuk developed the precursor state theory, whereby molecules would enter a precursor state at the interface between the solid adsorbent and adsorbate in the gaseous phase.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] From here, adsorbate molecules would either adsorb to the adsorbent or desorb into the gaseous phase.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The probability of adsorption occurring from the precursor state is dependent on the adsorbate's proximity to other adsorbate molecules that have already been adsorbed.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] If an adsorbate molecule enters the precursor state at a location that is remote from any other previously adsorbed adsorbate molecules, the sticking probability is reflected by the size of the SD constant.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] As SD is dictated by factors that are taken into account by the Langmuir model, SD can be assumed to be the adsorption rate constant.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] However, the rate constant for the Kisliuk model (*R*') is different from that of the Langmuir model, as *R*' is used to represent the impact of diffusion on monolayer formation and is proportional to the square root of the system's diffusion coefficient.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] As can be seen in the formula, the variation of *K* must be isosteric, that is, at constant coverage.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] that is to say, adsorption is more exothermic than liquefaction.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The adsorption of ensemble molecules on a surface or interface can be divided into two processes: adsorption and desorption.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] If the adsorption rate wins the desorption rate, the molecules will accumulate over time giving the adsorption curve over time.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] If the desorption rate is larger, the number of molecules on the surface will decrease over time.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The adsorption rate is dependent on the temperature, the diffusion rate of the solute (related to mean free path for pure gas), and the energy barrier between the molecule and the surface.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The diffusion and key elements of the adsorption rate can be calculated using Fick's laws of diffusion and the Einstein relation (kinetic theory).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] where A is the surface area (unit m2), C is the number concentration of the molecule in the bulk solution (unit #/m3), D is the diffusion constant (unit m2/s), and t is time (unit s).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Further simulations and analysis of this equation show that the square root dependence on the time is originated from the decrease of the concentrations near the surface under ideal adsorption conditions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Also, this equation only works for the beginning of the adsorption when a well-behaved concentration gradient forms near the surface.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Correction on the reduction of the adsorption area and slowing down of the concentration gradient evolution have to be considered over a longer time.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Under real experimental conditions, the flow and the small adsorption area always make the adsorption rate faster than what this equation predicted, and the energy barrier will either accelerate this rate by surface attraction or slow it down by surface repulsion.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Thus, the prediction from this equation is often a few to several orders of magnitude away from the experimental results.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The desorption of a molecule from the surface depends on the binding energy of the molecule to the surface and the temperature.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The typical overall adsorption rate is thus often a combined result of the adsorption and desorption.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Since 1980 two theories were worked on to explain adsorption and obtain equations that work.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] These two are referred to as the chi hypothesis, the quantum mechanical derivation, and excess surface work (ESW).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] where "ads" stands for "adsorbed", "m" stands for "monolayer equivalence" and "vap" is reference to the vapor pressure of the liquid adsorptive at the same temperature as the solid sample.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The plot of $n_{ads}$ adsorbed versus $\chi$ is referred to as the chi plot.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] For flat surfaces, the slope of the chi plot yields the surface area.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Empirically, this plot was noticed as being a very good fit to the isotherm by Michael Polanyi and also by Jan Hendrik de Boer and Cornelis Zwikker but not pursued.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] This was due to criticism in the former case by Albert Einstein and in the latter case by Brunauer.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] This flat surface equation may be used as a "standard curve" in the normal tradition of comparison curves, with the exception that the porous sample's early portion of the plot of $n_{ads}$ versus $\chi$ acts as a self-standard.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Ultramicroporous, microporous, and mesoporous conditions may be analyzed using this technique.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Typical standard deviations for full isotherm fits including porous samples are less than 2%.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Notice that in this description of physical adsorption, the entropy of adsorption is consistent with the Dubinin thermodynamic criterion, that is the entropy of adsorption from the liquid state to the adsorbed state is approximately zero.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Adsorbents are used usually in the form of spherical pellets, rods, moldings, or monoliths with a hydrodynamic radius between 0.25 and 5 millimetres (0.0098 and 0.1969 in).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] They must have high abrasion resistance, high thermal stability, and small pore diameters, which results in higher exposed surface area and hence high capacity for adsorption.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The adsorbents must also have a distinct pore structure that enables fast transport of the gaseous vapors.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Silica gel is a chemically inert, non-toxic, polar, and dimensionally stable (< 400 °C or 750 °F) amorphous form of SiO2.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] It is prepared by the reaction between sodium silicate and acetic acid, which is followed by a series of after-treatment processes such as aging, pickling, etc.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] These after-treatment methods results in various pore size distributions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Silica is used for drying of process air (e.g. oxygen, natural gas) and adsorption of heavy (polar) hydrocarbons from natural gas.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Zeolites are natural or synthetic crystalline aluminosilicates, which have a repeating pore network and release water at high temperature.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] They are manufactured by hydrothermal synthesis of sodium aluminosilicate or another silica source in an autoclave followed by ion exchange with certain cations (Na+, Li+, Ca2+, K+, NH4+).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The channel diameter of zeolite cages usually ranges from 2 to 9 Å.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The ion exchange process is followed by drying of the crystals, which can be pelletized with a binder to form macroporous pellets.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Zeolites are applied in drying of process air, CO2 removal from natural gas, CO removal from reforming gas, air separation, catalytic cracking, and catalytic synthesis and reforming.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Non-polar (siliceous) zeolites are synthesized from aluminum-free silica sources or by dealumination of aluminum-containing zeolites.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The dealumination process is done by treating the zeolite with steam at elevated temperatures, typically greater than 500 °C (930 °F).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] This high-temperature heat treatment breaks the aluminum-oxygen bonds and the aluminum atom is expelled from the zeolite framework.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The term "adsorption" itself was coined by Heinrich Kayser in 1881 in the context of uptake of gases by carbons.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Activated carbon is a highly porous, amorphous solid consisting of microcrystallites with a graphite lattice, usually prepared in small pellets or a powder.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] One of its main drawbacks is that it reacts with oxygen at moderate temperatures (over 300 °C (572 °F)).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Activated carbon can be manufactured from carbonaceous material, including coal (bituminous, subbituminous, and lignite), peat, wood, or nutshells (e.g., coconut).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The manufacturing process consists of two phases: carbonization and activation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The carbonization process includes drying and then heating to separate by-products, including tars and other hydrocarbons from the raw material, as well as to drive off any gases generated.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The process is completed by heating the material over 400 °C (750 °F) in an oxygen-free atmosphere that cannot support combustion.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The carbonized particles are then "activated" by exposing them to an oxidizing agent, usually steam or carbon dioxide, at high temperature.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] This agent burns off the pore-blocking structures created during the carbonization phase, and so they develop a porous, three-dimensional graphite lattice structure.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The size of the pores developed during activation is a function of the time that they spend in this stage.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Longer exposure times result in larger pore sizes.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The most popular aqueous phase carbons are bituminous based because of their hardness, abrasion resistance, pore size distribution, and low cost, but their effectiveness needs to be tested in each application to determine the optimal product.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Activated carbon is used for adsorption of organic substances and non-polar adsorbates and it is also usually used for waste gas (and waste water) treatment.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] It is the most widely used adsorbent since most of its chemical (e.g. surface groups) and physical properties (e.g. pore size distribution and surface area) can be tuned according to what is needed.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Its usefulness also derives from its large micropore (and sometimes mesopore) volume and the resulting high surface area.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Recent research works reported activated carbon as an effective agent to adsorb cationic species of toxic metals from multi-pollutant systems and also proposed possible adsorption mechanisms with supporting evidences.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The adsorption of water at surfaces is of broad importance in chemical engineering, materials science, and catalysis.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Also termed surface hydration, the presence of physically or chemically adsorbed water at the surfaces of solids plays an important role in governing interface properties, chemical reaction pathways, and catalytic performance in a wide range of systems.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] In the case of physically adsorbed water, surface hydration can be eliminated simply through drying at conditions of temperature and pressure allowing full vaporization of water.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The low cost ($200/ton) and high cycle rate (2,000 ×) of synthetic zeolites such as Linde 13X with water adsorbate has garnered much academic and commercial interest recently for use for thermal energy storage (TES), specifically of low-grade solar and waste heat.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Several pilot projects have been funded in the EU from 2000 to the present (2020).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The basic concept is to store solar thermal energy as chemical latent energy in the zeolite.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Typically, hot dry air from flat plate solar collectors is made to flow through a bed of zeolite such that any water adsorbate present is driven off.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Storage can be diurnal, weekly, monthly, or even seasonal depending on the volume of the zeolite and the area of the solar thermal panels.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] When heat is called for during the night, or sunless hours, or winter, humidified air flows through the zeolite.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] As the humidity is adsorbed by the zeolite, heat is released to the air and subsequently to the building space.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] This form of TES, with specific use of zeolites, was first taught by John Guerra in 1978.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Typical adsorbents proposed for carbon capture and storage are zeolites and MOFs.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The customization of adsorbents makes them a potentially attractive alternative to absorption.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Because adsorbents can be regenerated by temperature or pressure swing, this step can be less energy intensive than absorption regeneration methods.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Major problems that are present with adsorption cost in carbon capture are: regenerating the adsorbent, mass ratio, solvent/MOF, cost of adsorbent, production of the adsorbent, lifetime of adsorbent.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] In sorption enhanced water gas shift (SEWGS) technology a pre-combustion carbon capture process, based on solid adsorption, is combined with the water-gas shift reaction (WGS) in order to produce a high pressure hydrogen stream.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The CO2 stream produced can be stored or used for other industrial processes.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Protein adsorption is a process that has a fundamental role in the field of biomaterials.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Indeed, biomaterial surfaces in contact with biological media, such as blood or serum, are immediately coated by proteins.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Therefore, living cells do not interact directly with the biomaterial surface, but with the adsorbed proteins layer.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] This protein layer mediates the interaction between biomaterials and cells, translating biomaterial physical and chemical properties into a "biological language".
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] In fact, cell membrane receptors bind to protein layer bioactive sites and these receptor-protein binding events are transduced, through the cell membrane, in a manner that stimulates specific intracellular processes that then determine cell adhesion, shape, growth, and differentiation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Protein adsorption is influenced by many surface properties such as surface wettability, surface chemical composition, and surface nanometre-scale morphology.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Surfactant adsorption is a similar phenomenon, but utilising surfactant molecules in the place of proteins.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Combining an adsorbent with a refrigerant, adsorption chillers use heat to provide a cooling effect.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] This heat, in the form of hot water, may come from any number of industrial sources including waste heat from industrial processes, prime heat from solar thermal installations or from the exhaust or water jacket heat of a piston engine or turbine.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Although there are similarities between adsorption chillers and absorption refrigeration, the former is based on the interaction between gases and solids.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The adsorption chamber of the chiller is filled with a solid material (for example zeolite, silica gel, alumina, active carbon or certain types of metal salts), which in its neutral state has adsorbed the refrigerant.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] When heated, the solid desorbs (releases) refrigerant vapour, which subsequently is cooled and liquefied.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] This liquid refrigerant then provides a cooling effect at the evaporator from its enthalpy of vaporization.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] In the final stage the refrigerant vapour is (re)adsorbed into the solid.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] As an adsorption chiller requires no compressor, it is relatively quiet.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Portal site mediated adsorption is a model for site-selective activated gas adsorption in metallic catalytic systems that contain a variety of different adsorption sites.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] In such systems, low-coordination "edge and corner" defect-like sites can exhibit significantly lower adsorption enthalpies than high-coordination (basal plane) sites.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] As a result, these sites can serve as "portals" for very rapid adsorption to the rest of the surface.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The phenomenon relies on the common "spillover" effect (described below), where certain adsorbed species exhibit high mobility on some surfaces.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The model explains seemingly inconsistent observations of gas adsorption thermodynamics and kinetics in catalytic systems where surfaces can exist in a range of coordination structures, and it has been successfully applied to bimetallic catalytic systems where synergistic activity is observed.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] In contrast to pure spillover, portal site adsorption refers to surface diffusion to adjacent adsorption sites, not to non-adsorptive support surfaces.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The model appears to have been first proposed for carbon monoxide on silica-supported platinum by Brandt *et al.* (1993).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] A similar, but independent model was developed by King and co-workers to describe hydrogen adsorption on silica-supported alkali promoted ruthenium, silver-ruthenium, and copper-ruthenium bimetallic catalysts.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The same group applied the model to CO hydrogenation (Fischer–Tropsch synthesis).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Zupanc *et al.* (2002) subsequently confirmed the same model for hydrogen adsorption on magnesia-supported caesium-ruthenium bimetallic catalysts.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Trens *et al.* (2009) have similarly described CO surface diffusion on carbon-supported Pt particles of varying morphology.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The presence of the metal serves as a lower-energy pathway for gaseous species to first adsorb to the metal and then diffuse on the support surface.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] This is possible because the adsorbed species attains a lower energy state once it has adsorbed to the metal, thus lowering the activation barrier between the gas phase species and the support-adsorbed species.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Hydrogen spillover is the most common example of an adsorptive spillover.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] In the case of hydrogen, adsorption is most often accompanied with dissociation of molecular hydrogen (H2) to atomic hydrogen (H), followed by spillover of the hydrogen atoms present.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The spillover effect has been used to explain many observations in heterogeneous catalysis and adsorption.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Adsorption of molecules onto polymer surfaces is central to a number of applications, including development of non-stick coatings and in various biomedical devices.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Polymers may also be adsorbed to surfaces through polyelectrolyte adsorption.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Adsorption is the beginning of viral entry, which is the earliest stage of infection in the viral life cycle.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The next steps are penetration, uncoating, synthesis (transcription if needed, and translation), and release.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The virus replication cycle, in this respect, is similar for all types of viruses.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Factors such as transcription may or may not be needed if the virus is able to integrate its genomic information in the cell's nucleus, or if the virus can replicate itself directly within the cell's cytoplasm.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] The game of *Tetris* is a puzzle game in which blocks of 4 are adsorbed onto a surface during game play.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/adsorption] Scientists have used *Tetris* blocks "as a proxy for molecules with a complex shape" and their "adsorption on a flat surface" for studying the thermodynamics of nanoparticles.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] An **aerosol** is a suspension of fine solid particles or liquid droplets in air or another gas.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Aerosols can be generated from natural or human causes.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The scientific term *aerosol* refers to the mixture of particulates in gas, and not to the particulate matter alone.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The liquid or solid particles in an aerosol have diameters typically less than 1 μm.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Larger particles with a significant settling speed make the mixture a suspension, although the distinction is not clear.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Examples of natural aerosols are fog, mist, and dust from geological or biological sources.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Certain infections spread by means of small droplets in the breath, sometimes called bioaerosols.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Several types of atmospheric aerosol have a significant effect on Earth's climate: volcanic, desert dust, sea-salt, originating from biogenic sources and human-made.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Volcanic aerosol forms in the stratosphere after an eruption as droplets of sulfuric acid that can prevail for up to two years, and reflect sunlight, lowering temperature.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Desert dust, mineral particles blown to high altitudes, absorb heat and may be responsible for inhibiting storm cloud formation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] In everyday language, *aerosol* often refers to a dispensing system that delivers a consumer product from a spray can.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Other examples of human caused aerosols include perfume from atomizers, medical treatments for respiratory illnesses, dust from material or industrial sources, smoke, irrigation mist, sprayed pesticides, particulate air pollutants, and mist from the discharge at hydroelectric dams.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Human-made sulfate aerosols, primarily from burning oil and coal, affect the behavior of clouds.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] When aerosols absorb pollutants, it facilitates the deposition of pollutants to the surface of the earth as well as to bodies of water.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] This has the potential to be damaging to both the environment and human health.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Ship tracks are clouds that form around the exhaust released by ships into the still ocean air.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Water molecules collect around the tiny particles (aerosols) from exhaust to form a cloud seed.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] More and more water accumulates on the seed until a visible cloud is formed.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] In the case of ship tracks, the cloud seeds are stretched over a long narrow path where the wind has blown the ship's exhaust, so the resulting clouds resemble long strings over the ocean.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The warming caused by human-produced greenhouse gases has been somewhat offset by the cooling effect of human-produced aerosols.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] In 2020, regulations on fuel significantly cut sulfur dioxide emissions from international shipping by approximately 80%, leading to an unexpected global geoengineering termination shock.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Aerosol is defined as a suspension system of solid or liquid particles in a gas.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] An aerosol includes both the particles and the suspending gas, which is usually air.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Meteorologists and climatologists often refer to them as particle matter, while the classification in sizes ranges like PM2.5 or PM10, is useful in the field of atmospheric pollution as these size range play a role in ascertain the harmful effects in human health.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Donnan presumably first used the term *aerosol* during World War I to describe an aero-solution, clouds of microscopic particles in air.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] This term developed analogously to the term hydrosol, a colloid system with water as the dispersed medium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] *Primary aerosols* contain particles introduced directly into the gas; *secondary aerosols* form through gas-to-particle conversion.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Key aerosol groups include sulfates, organic carbon, black carbon, nitrates, mineral dust, and sea salt, they usually clump together to form a complex mixture.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Various types of aerosol, classified according to physical form and how they were generated, include dust, fume, mist, smoke and fog.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] There are several measures of aerosol concentration.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Environmental science and environmental health often use the *mass concentration* (*M*), defined as the mass of particulate matter per unit volume, in units such as μg/m3.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Also commonly used is the *number concentration* (*N*), the number of particles per unit volume, in units such as number per m3 or number per cm3.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Particle size has a major influence on particle properties, and the aerosol particle radius or diameter (*dp*) is a key property used to characterise aerosols.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] A *monodisperse* aerosol, producible in the laboratory, contains particles of uniform size.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Most aerosols, however, as *polydisperse* colloidal systems, exhibit a range of particle sizes.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Liquid droplets are almost always nearly spherical, but scientists use an *equivalent diameter* to characterize the properties of various shapes of solid particles, some very irregular.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The equivalent diameter is the diameter of a spherical particle with the same value of some physical property as the irregular particle.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The *equivalent volume diameter* (*de*) is defined as the diameter of a sphere of the same volume as that of the irregular particle.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Also commonly used is the aerodynamic diameter, *da*.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Several types of atmospheric aerosol have a significant effect on Earth's climate: volcanic, desert dust, sea-salt, that originating from biogenic sources and human-made.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Although all hydrometeors, solid and liquid, can be described as aerosols, a distinction is commonly made between such dispersions (i.e. clouds and precipitation) containing relatively large water drops or ice crystals, and aerosol particles.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The presence of aerosols in the Earth's atmosphere can influence its climate, as well as human health.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Volcanic eruptions release large amounts of sulphuric acid, hydrogen sulfide and hydrochloric acid into the atmosphere.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] These gases represent aerosols and eventually return to earth as acid rain, having a number of adverse effects on the environment and human life.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Aerosols interact with the Earth's energy budget in two ways, directly and indirectly.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Aerosol particles with an effective diameter smaller than 10 μm can enter the bronchi, while the ones with an effective diameter smaller than 2.5 μm can enter as far as the gas exchange region in the lungs, which can be hazardous to human health.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] For a monodisperse aerosol, a single number—the particle diameter—suffices to describe the size of the particles.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] However, more complicated particle-size distributions describe the sizes of the particles in a polydisperse aerosol.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] This distribution defines the relative amounts of particles, sorted according to size.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] One approach to defining the particle size distribution uses a list of the sizes of every particle in a sample.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] However, this approach proves tedious to ascertain in aerosols with millions of particles and awkward to use.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Another approach splits the size range into intervals and finds the number (or proportion) of particles in each interval.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The particle size distribution can be approximated.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The normal distribution usually does not suitably describe particle size distributions in aerosols because of the skewness associated with a long tail of larger particles.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Also for a quantity that varies over a large range, as many aerosol sizes do, the width of the distribution implies negative particles sizes, which is not physically realistic.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] However, the normal distribution can be suitable for some aerosols, such as test aerosols, certain pollen grains and spores.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The log-normal distribution has no negative values, can cover a wide range of values, and fits many observed size distributions reasonably well.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] For low values of the Reynolds number (<1), true for most aerosol motion, Stokes' law describes the force of resistance on a solid spherical particle in a fluid.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] However, Stokes' law is only valid when the velocity of the gas at the surface of the particle is zero.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] For small particles (< 1 μm) that characterize aerosols, however, this assumption fails.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] To account for this failure, one can introduce the Cunningham correction factor, always greater than 1.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] This allows us to calculate the terminal velocity of a particle undergoing gravitational settling in still air.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] is the terminal settling velocity of the particle.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The terminal velocity can also be derived for other kinds of forces.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] If Stokes' law holds, then the resistance to motion is directly proportional to speed.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] To account for the effect of the shape of non-spherical particles, a correction factor known as the *dynamic shape factor* is applied to Stokes' law.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The aerodynamic diameter of an irregular particle is defined as the diameter of the spherical particle with a density of 1000 kg/m3 and the same settling velocity as the irregular particle.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] One can apply the aerodynamic diameter to particulate pollutants or to inhaled drugs to predict where in the respiratory tract such particles deposit.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Pharmaceutical companies typically use aerodynamic diameter, not geometric diameter, to characterize particles in inhalable drugs.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The previous discussion focused on single aerosol particles.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] In contrast, *aerosol dynamics* explains the evolution of complete aerosol populations.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The concentrations of particles will change over time as a result of many processes.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] External processes that move particles outside a volume of gas under study include diffusion, gravitational settling, and electric charges and other external forces that cause particle migration.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] A second set of processes internal to a given volume of gas include particle formation (nucleation), evaporation, chemical reaction, and coagulation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] A differential equation called the *Aerosol General Dynamic Equation* (GDE) characterizes the evolution of the number density of particles in an aerosol due to these processes.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] As particles and droplets in an aerosol collide with one another, they may undergo coalescence or aggregation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] This process leads to a change in the aerosol particle-size distribution, with the mode increasing in diameter as total number of particles decreases.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] On occasion, particles may shatter apart into numerous smaller particles; however, this process usually occurs primarily in particles too large for consideration as aerosols.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] where $\lambda$ is the mean free path of the suspending gas and d is the diameter of the particle.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] For particles in the *free molecular regime*, *Kn* >> 1; particles small compared to the mean free path of the suspending gas.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] In this regime, particles interact with the suspending gas through a series of "ballistic" collisions with gas molecules.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] As such, they behave similarly to gas molecules, tending to follow streamlines and diffusing rapidly through Brownian motion.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] where *a* is the particle radius, *P*∞ and *PA* are the pressures far from the droplet and at the surface of the droplet respectively, *kb* is the Boltzmann constant, *T* is the temperature, *CA* is mean thermal velocity and *α* is mass accommodation coefficient.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The derivation of this equation assumes constant pressure and constant diffusion coefficient.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Particles are in the *continuum regime* when Kn << 1.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] In this regime, the particles are big compared to the mean free path of the suspending gas, meaning that the suspending gas acts as a continuous fluid flowing round the particle.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The *transition regime* contains all the particles in between the free molecular and continuum regimes or *Kn* ≈ 1.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The forces experienced by a particle are a complex combination of interactions with individual gas molecules and macroscopic interactions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] where *I*cont is the mass flux in the continuum regime.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] This formula is called the Fuchs-Sutugin interpolation formula.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] These equations do not take into account the heat release effect.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Aerosol partitioning theory governs condensation on and evaporation from an aerosol surface, respectively.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Condensation of mass causes the mode of the particle-size distributions of the aerosol to increase; conversely, evaporation causes the mode to decrease.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Nucleation is the process of forming aerosol mass from the condensation of a gaseous precursor, specifically a vapor.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Net condensation of the vapor requires supersaturation, a partial pressure greater than its vapor pressure.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Chemical reactions may increase the partial pressure of a gas or lower its vapor pressure.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The addition of additional vapor to the system may lower the equilibrium vapor pressure according to Raoult's law.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] There are two types of nucleation processes.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Gases preferentially condense onto surfaces of pre-existing aerosol particles, known as **heterogeneous nucleation**.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] This process causes the diameter at the mode of particle-size distribution to increase with constant number concentration.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] With sufficiently high supersaturation and no suitable surfaces, particles may condense in the absence of a pre-existing surface, known as **homogeneous nucleation**.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] This results in the addition of very small, rapidly growing particles to the particle-size distribution.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Water coats particles in aerosols, making them *activated*, usually in the context of forming a cloud droplet (such as natural cloud seeding by aerosols from trees in a forest).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Following the Kelvin equation (based on the curvature of liquid droplets), smaller particles need a higher ambient relative humidity to maintain equilibrium than larger particles do.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] where $p_{s}$ is the saturation vapor pressure above a particle at equilibrium (around a curved liquid droplet), *p*0 is the saturation vapor pressure (flat surface of the same liquid) and *S* is the saturation ratio.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] where *rp* droplet radius, *σ* surface tension of droplet, *ρ* density of liquid, *M* molar mass, *T* temperature, and *R* molar gas constant.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Aerosols can either be measured in-situ or with remote sensing techniques either ground-based on airborne-based.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Particles can deposit in the nose, mouth, pharynx and larynx (the head airways region), deeper within the respiratory tract (from the trachea to the terminal bronchioles), or in the alveolar region.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The location of deposition of aerosol particles within the respiratory system strongly determines the health effects of exposure to such aerosols.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] This phenomenon led people to invent aerosol samplers that select a subset of the aerosol particles that reach certain parts of the respiratory system.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Examples of these subsets of the particle-size distribution of an aerosol, important in occupational health, include the inhalable, thoracic, and respirable fractions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The fraction that can enter each part of the respiratory system depends on the deposition of particles in the upper parts of the airway.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The inhalable fraction of particles, defined as the proportion of particles originally in the air that can enter the nose or mouth, depends on external wind speed and direction and on the particle-size distribution by aerodynamic diameter.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The thoracic fraction is the proportion of the particles in ambient aerosol that can reach the thorax or chest region.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The respirable fraction is the proportion of particles in the air that can reach the alveolar region.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] To measure the respirable fraction of particles in air, a pre-collector is used with a sampling filter.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The pre-collector excludes particles as the airways remove particles from inhaled air.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The sampling filter collects the particles for measurement.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] It is common to use cyclonic separation for the pre-collector, but other techniques include impactors, horizontal elutriators, and large pore membrane filters.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] Two alternative size-selective criteria, often used in atmospheric monitoring, are PM10 and PM2.5.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] PM10 is defined by ISO as *particles which pass through a size-selective inlet with a 50% efficiency cut-off at 10 μm aerodynamic diameter* and PM2.5 as *particles which pass through a size-selective inlet with a 50% efficiency cut-off at 2.5 μm aerodynamic diameter*.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] PM10 corresponds to the "thoracic convention" as defined in ISO 7708:1995, Clause 6; PM2.5 corresponds to the "high-risk respirable convention" as defined in ISO 7708:1995, 7.1.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/aerosol] The United States Environmental Protection Agency replaced the older standards for particulate matter based on Total Suspended Particulate with another standard based on PM10 in 1987 and then introduced standards for PM2.5 (also known as fine particulate matter) in 1997.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The **alkali metals** consist of the chemical elements lithium (Li), sodium (Na), potassium (K), rubidium (Rb), caesium (Cs), and francium (Fr).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Together with hydrogen they constitute group 1, which lies in the s-block of the periodic table.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] All alkali metals have their outermost electron in an s-orbital: this shared electron configuration results in them having very similar characteristic properties.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Indeed, the alkali metals provide the best example of group trends in properties in the periodic table, with elements exhibiting well-characterised homologous behaviour.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] This family of elements is also known as the **lithium family** after its leading element.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The alkali metals are all shiny, soft, highly reactive metals at standard temperature and pressure and readily lose their outermost electron to form cations with charge +1.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] They can all be cut easily with a knife due to their softness, exposing a shiny surface that tarnishes rapidly in air due to oxidation by atmospheric moisture and oxygen (and in the case of lithium, nitrogen).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Because of their high reactivity, they must be stored under oil to prevent reaction with air, and are found naturally only in salts and never as the free elements.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium, the fifth alkali metal, is the most reactive of all the metals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] All the alkali metals react with water, with the heavier alkali metals reacting more vigorously than the lighter ones.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Experiments have been conducted to attempt the synthesis of element 119, which is likely to be the next member of the group; none were successful.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Most alkali metals have many different applications.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] One of the best-known applications of the pure elements is the use of rubidium and caesium in atomic clocks, of which caesium atomic clocks form the basis of the second.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] A common application of the compounds of sodium is the sodium-vapour lamp, which emits light very efficiently.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Table salt, or sodium chloride, has been used since antiquity.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Lithium finds use as a psychiatric medication and as an anode in lithium batteries.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Sodium, potassium and possibly lithium are essential elements, having major biological roles as electrolytes, and although the other alkali metals are not essential, they also have various effects on the body, both beneficial and harmful.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Sodium compounds have been known since ancient times; salt (sodium chloride) has been an important commodity in human activities.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] While potash has been used since ancient times, it was not understood for most of its history to be a fundamentally different substance from sodium mineral salts.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Georg Ernst Stahl obtained experimental evidence which led him to suggest the fundamental difference of sodium and potassium salts in 1702, and Henri-Louis Duhamel du Monceau was able to prove this difference in 1736.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The exact chemical composition of potassium and sodium compounds, and the status as chemical element of potassium and sodium, was not known then, and thus Antoine Lavoisier did not include either alkali in his list of chemical elements in 1789.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Pure potassium was first isolated in 1807 in England by Humphry Davy, who derived it from caustic potash (KOH, potassium hydroxide) by the use of electrolysis of the molten salt with the newly invented voltaic pile.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Previous attempts at electrolysis of the aqueous salt were unsuccessful due to potassium's extreme reactivity.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Potassium was the first metal that was isolated by electrolysis.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Later that same year, Davy reported extraction of sodium from the similar substance caustic soda (NaOH, lye) by a similar technique, demonstrating the elements, and thus the salts, to be different.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Petalite (LiAlSi4O10) was discovered in 1800 by the Brazilian chemist José Bonifácio de Andrada in a mine on the island of Utö, Sweden.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] However, it was not until 1817 that Johan August Arfwedson, then working in the laboratory of the chemist Jöns Jacob Berzelius, detected the presence of a new element while analysing petalite ore.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] This new element was noted by him to form compounds similar to those of sodium and potassium, though its carbonate and hydroxide were less soluble in water and more alkaline than the other alkali metals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] He named the metal inside the material *lithium*.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Lithium, sodium, and potassium were part of the discovery of periodicity, as they are among a series of triads of elements in the same group that were noted by Johann Wolfgang Döbereiner in 1850 as having similar properties.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Rubidium and caesium were the first elements to be discovered using the spectroscope, invented in 1859 by Robert Bunsen and Gustav Kirchhoff.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The next year, they discovered caesium in the mineral water from Bad Dürkheim, Germany.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Their discovery of rubidium came the following year in Heidelberg, Germany, finding it in the mineral lepidolite.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The names of rubidium and caesium come from the most prominent lines in their emission spectra: a bright red line for rubidium (from the Latin word *rubidus*, meaning dark red or bright red), and a sky-blue line for caesium (derived from the Latin word *caesius*, meaning sky-blue).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] His version put all the alkali metals then known (lithium to caesium), as well as copper, silver, and thallium (which show the +1 oxidation state characteristic of the alkali metals), together into a group.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] His table placed hydrogen with the halogens.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] After 1869, Dmitri Mendeleev proposed his periodic table placing lithium at the top of a group with sodium, potassium, rubidium, caesium, and thallium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Two years later, Mendeleev revised his table, placing hydrogen in group 1 above lithium, and also moving thallium to the boron group.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] In this 1871 version, copper, silver, and gold were placed twice, once as part of group IB, and once as part of a "group VIII" encompassing today's groups 8 to 11.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] After the introduction of the 18-column table, the group IB elements were moved to their current position in the d-block, while alkali metals were left in *group IA*.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Later the group's name was changed to *group 1* in 1988.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The trivial name "alkali metals" comes from the fact that the hydroxides of the group 1 elements are all strong alkalis when dissolved in water.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] There were at least four erroneous and incomplete discoveries before Marguerite Perey of the Curie Institute in Paris, France discovered francium in 1939 by purifying a sample of actinium-227, which had been reported to have a decay energy of 220 keV.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] However, Perey noticed decay particles with an energy level below 80 keV.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Perey thought this decay activity might have been caused by a previously unidentified decay product, one that was separated during purification, but emerged again out of the pure actinium-227.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Various tests eliminated the possibility of the unknown element being thorium, radium, lead, bismuth, or thallium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The new product exhibited chemical properties of an alkali metal (such as coprecipitating with caesium salts), which led Perey to believe that it was element 87, caused by the alpha decay of actinium-227.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Perey then attempted to determine the proportion of beta decay to alpha decay in actinium-227.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Her first test put the alpha branching at 0.6%, a figure that she later revised to 1%.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The next element below francium (eka-francium) in the periodic table would be ununennium (Uue), element 119.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The synthesis of ununennium was first attempted in 1985 by bombarding a target of einsteinium-254 with calcium-48 ions at the superHILAC accelerator at the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory in Berkeley, California.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] No atoms were identified, leading to a limiting yield of 300 nb.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] However, given that ununennium is only the first period 8 element on the extended periodic table, it may well be discovered in the near future through other reactions, and indeed an attempt to synthesise it is currently ongoing in Japan.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Currently, none of the period 8 elements has been discovered yet, and it is also possible, due to drip instabilities, that only the lower period 8 elements, up to around element 128, are physically possible.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] No attempts at synthesis have been made for any heavier alkali metals: due to their extremely high atomic number, they would require new, more powerful methods and technology to make.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The Oddo–Harkins rule holds that elements with even atomic numbers are more common than those with odd atomic numbers, with the exception of hydrogen and beryllium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] This rule argues that elements with odd atomic numbers have one unpaired proton and are more likely to capture another, thus increasing their atomic number.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] In elements with even atomic numbers, protons are paired, with each member of the pair offsetting the spin of the other, enhancing stability.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] All the alkali metals have odd atomic numbers and they are not as common as the elements with even atomic numbers adjacent to them (the noble gases and the alkaline earth metals) in the Solar System.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The heavier alkali metals are also less abundant than the lighter ones as the alkali metals from rubidium onward can only be synthesised in supernovae and not in stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The Earth formed from the same cloud of matter that formed the Sun, but the planets acquired different compositions during the formation and evolution of the Solar System.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] In turn, the natural history of the Earth caused parts of this planet to have differing concentrations of the elements.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The mass of the Earth is approximately 5.98×1024 kg.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Due to planetary differentiation, the core region is believed to be primarily composed of iron (88.8%), with smaller amounts of nickel (5.8%), sulfur (4.5%), and less than 1% trace elements.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The alkali metals, due to their high reactivity, do not occur naturally in pure form in nature.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] They are lithophiles and therefore remain close to the Earth's surface because they combine readily with oxygen and so associate strongly with silica, forming relatively low-density minerals that do not sink down into the Earth's core.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Potassium, rubidium and caesium are also incompatible elements due to their large ionic radii.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Sodium and potassium are very abundant on Earth, both being among the ten most common elements in Earth's crust; sodium makes up approximately 2.6% of the Earth's crust measured by weight, making it the sixth most abundant element overall and the most abundant alkali metal.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Potassium makes up approximately 1.5% of the Earth's crust and is the seventh most abundant element.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Sodium is found in many different minerals, of which the most common is ordinary salt (sodium chloride), which occurs in vast quantities dissolved in seawater.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Other solid deposits include halite, amphibole, cryolite, nitratine, and zeolite.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Many of these solid deposits occur as a result of ancient seas evaporating, which still occurs now in places such as Utah's Great Salt Lake and the Dead Sea.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Despite its chemical similarity, lithium typically does not occur together with sodium or potassium due to its smaller size.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Due to its relatively low reactivity, it can be found in seawater in large amounts; it is estimated that lithium concentration in seawater is approximately 0.14 to 0.25 parts per million (ppm) or 25 micromolar.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Its diagonal relationship with magnesium often allows it to replace magnesium in ferromagnesium minerals, where its crustal concentration is about 18 ppm, comparable to that of gallium and niobium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Commercially, the most important lithium mineral is spodumene, which occurs in large deposits worldwide.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Rubidium is approximately as abundant as zinc and more abundant than copper.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] It occurs naturally in the minerals leucite, pollucite, carnallite, zinnwaldite, and lepidolite, although none of these contain only rubidium and no other alkali metals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium is more abundant than some commonly known elements, such as antimony, cadmium, tin, and tungsten, but is much less abundant than rubidium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Francium-223, the only naturally occurring isotope of francium, is the product of the alpha decay of actinium-227 and can be found in trace amounts in uranium minerals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] In a given sample of uranium, there is estimated to be only one francium atom for every 1018 uranium atoms.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] It has been calculated that there are at most 30 grams of francium in the earth's crust at any time, due to its extremely short half-life of 22 minutes.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The physical and chemical properties of the alkali metals can be readily explained by their having an ns1 valence electron configuration, which results in weak metallic bonding.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Hence, all the alkali metals are soft and have low densities, melting and boiling points, as well as heats of sublimation, vaporisation, and dissociation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] They all crystallise in the body-centered cubic crystal structure, and have distinctive flame colours because their outer s electron is very easily excited.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Indeed, these flame test colours are the most common way of identifying them since all their salts with common ions are soluble.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The ns1 configuration also results in the alkali metals having very large atomic and ionic radii, as well as very high thermal and electrical conductivity.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Their chemistry is dominated by the loss of their lone valence electron in the outermost s-orbital to form the +1 oxidation state, due to the ease of ionising this electron and the very high second ionisation energy.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Most of the chemistry has been observed only for the first five members of the group.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The chemistry of francium is not well established due to its extreme radioactivity; thus, the presentation of its properties here is limited.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] What little is known about francium shows that it is very close in behaviour to caesium, as expected.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The physical properties of francium are even sketchier because the bulk element has never been observed; hence any data that may be found in the literature are certainly speculative extrapolations.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The alkali metals are more similar to each other than the elements in any other group are to each other.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Indeed, the similarity is so great that it is quite difficult to separate potassium, rubidium, and caesium, due to their similar ionic radii; lithium and sodium are more distinct.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] For instance, when moving down the table, all known alkali metals show increasing atomic radius, decreasing electronegativity, increasing reactivity, and decreasing melting and boiling points as well as heats of fusion and vaporisation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] In general, their densities increase when moving down the table, with the exception that potassium is less dense than sodium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] One of the very few properties of the alkali metals that does not display a very smooth trend is their reduction potentials: lithium's value is anomalous, being more negative than the others.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The stable alkali metals are all silver-coloured metals except for caesium, which has a pale golden tint: it is one of only three metals that are clearly coloured (the other two being copper and gold).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Additionally, the heavy alkaline earth metals calcium, strontium, and barium, as well as the divalent lanthanides europium and ytterbium, are pale yellow, though the colour is much less prominent than it is for caesium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Their lustre tarnishes rapidly in air due to oxidation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] All the alkali metals are highly reactive and are never found in elemental forms in nature.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Because of this, they are usually stored in mineral oil or kerosene (paraffin oil).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] They react aggressively with the halogens to form the alkali metal halides, which are white ionic crystalline compounds that are all soluble in water except lithium fluoride (LiF).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The alkali metals also react with water to form strongly alkaline hydroxides and thus should be handled with great care.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The heavier alkali metals react more vigorously than the lighter ones; for example, when dropped into water, caesium produces a larger explosion than potassium if the same number of moles of each metal is used.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The alkali metals have the lowest first ionisation energies in their respective periods of the periodic table because of their low effective nuclear charge and the ability to attain a noble gas configuration by losing just one electron.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Not only do the alkali metals react with water, but also with proton donors like alcohols and phenols, gaseous ammonia, and alkynes, the last demonstrating the phenomenal degree of their reactivity.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Their great power as reducing agents makes them very useful in liberating other metals from their oxides or halides.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The second ionisation energy of all of the alkali metals is very high as it is in a full shell that is also closer to the nucleus; thus, they almost always lose a single electron, forming cations.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The alkalide anions have filled s-subshells, which gives them enough stability to exist.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] All the stable alkali metals except lithium are known to be able to form alkalides, and the alkalides have much theoretical interest due to their unusual stoichiometry and low ionisation potentials.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Alkalides are chemically similar to the electrides, which are salts with trapped electrons acting as anions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] In aqueous solution, the alkali metal ions form aqua ions of the formula [M(H2O)*n*]+, where *n* is the solvation number.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Their coordination numbers and shapes agree well with those expected from their ionic radii.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] In aqueous solution the water molecules directly attached to the metal ion are said to belong to the first coordination sphere, also known as the first, or primary, solvation shell.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The bond between a water molecule and the metal ion is a dative covalent bond, with the oxygen atom donating both electrons to the bond.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Each coordinated water molecule may be attached by hydrogen bonds to other water molecules.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The latter are said to reside in the second coordination sphere.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] There are also probably six water molecules in the primary solvation sphere of the sodium ion, forming the octahedral [Na(H2O)6]+ ion.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The chemistry of lithium shows several differences from that of the rest of the group as the small Li+ cation polarises anions and gives its compounds a more covalent character.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Lithium and magnesium have a diagonal relationship due to their similar atomic radii, so that they show some similarities.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] For example, lithium forms a stable nitride, a property common among all the alkaline earth metals (magnesium's group) but unique among the alkali metals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] In addition, among their respective groups, only lithium and magnesium form organometallic compounds with significant covalent character (e.g.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Lithium fluoride is the only alkali metal halide that is poorly soluble in water, and lithium hydroxide is the only alkali metal hydroxide that is not deliquescent.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Conversely, lithium perchlorate and other lithium salts with large anions that cannot be polarised are much more stable than the analogous compounds of the other alkali metals, probably because Li+ has a high solvation energy.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] This effect also means that most simple lithium salts are commonly encountered in hydrated form, because the anhydrous forms are extremely hygroscopic: this allows salts like lithium chloride and lithium bromide to be used in dehumidifiers and air-conditioners.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Francium is also predicted to show some differences due to its high atomic weight, causing its electrons to travel at considerable fractions of the speed of light and thus making relativistic effects more prominent.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Thus, contrary to expectation, caesium is the most reactive of the alkali metals, not francium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Some of the few properties of francium that have been predicted taking relativity into account are the electron affinity (47.2 kJ/mol) and the enthalpy of dissociation of the Fr2 molecule (42.1 kJ/mol).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The CsFr molecule is polarised as Cs+Fr−, showing that the 7s subshell of francium is much more strongly affected by relativistic effects than the 6s subshell of caesium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Additionally, francium superoxide (FrO2) is expected to have significant covalent character, unlike the other alkali metal superoxides, because of bonding contributions from the 6p electrons of francium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] All the alkali metals have odd atomic numbers; hence, their isotopes must be either odd–odd (both proton and neutron number are odd) or odd–even (proton number is odd, but neutron number is even).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Odd–odd nuclei have even mass numbers, whereas odd–even nuclei have odd mass numbers.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Odd–odd primordial nuclides are rare because most odd–odd nuclei are highly unstable with respect to beta decay, because the decay products are even–even, and are therefore more strongly bound, due to nuclear pairing effects.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Due to the great rarity of odd–odd nuclei, almost all the primordial isotopes of the alkali metals are odd–even (the exceptions being the light stable isotope lithium-6 and the long-lived radioisotope potassium-40).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] An effect of the instability of an odd number of either type of nucleons is that odd-numbered elements, such as the alkali metals, tend to have fewer stable isotopes than even-numbered elements.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Of the 26 monoisotopic elements that have only a single stable isotope, all but one have an odd atomic number and all but one also have an even number of neutrons.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Beryllium is the single exception to both rules, due to its low atomic number.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium was also thought to be radioactive in the early 20th century, although it has no naturally occurring radioisotopes.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] (Francium had not been discovered yet at that time.) The natural long-lived radioisotope of potassium, potassium-40, makes up about 0.012% of natural potassium, and thus natural potassium is weakly radioactive.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] This natural radioactivity became a basis for a mistaken claim of the discovery for element 87 (the next alkali metal after caesium) in 1925.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Natural rubidium is similarly slightly radioactive, with 27.83% being the long-lived radioisotope rubidium-87.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium-137, with a half-life of 30.17 years, is one of the two principal medium-lived fission products, along with strontium-90, which are responsible for most of the radioactivity of spent nuclear fuel after several years of cooling, up to several hundred years after use.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] It constitutes most of the radioactivity still left from the Chernobyl accident.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium-137 undergoes high-energy beta decay and eventually becomes stable barium-137.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] It is a strong emitter of gamma radiation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium-137 has a very low rate of neutron capture and cannot be feasibly disposed of in this way, but must be allowed to decay.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Caesium-137 has been used as a tracer in hydrologic studies, analogous to the use of tritium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Small amounts of caesium-134 and caesium-137 were released into the environment during nearly all nuclear weapon tests and some nuclear accidents, most notably the Goiânia accident and the Chernobyl disaster.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] As of 2005, caesium-137 is the principal source of radiation in the zone of alienation around the Chernobyl nuclear power plant.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The atomic radii of the alkali metals increase going down the group.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Because of the shielding effect, when an atom has more than one electron shell, each electron feels electric repulsion from the other electrons as well as electric attraction from the nucleus.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] In the alkali metals, the outermost electron only feels a net charge of +1, as some of the nuclear charge (which is equal to the atomic number) is cancelled by the inner electrons; the number of inner electrons of an alkali metal is always one less than the nuclear charge.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Therefore, the only factor which affects the atomic radius of the alkali metals is the number of electron shells.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Since this number increases down the group, the atomic radius must also increase down the group.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The ionic radii of the alkali metals are much smaller than their atomic radii.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] This is because the outermost electron of the alkali metals is in a different electron shell than the inner electrons, and thus when it is removed the resulting atom has one fewer electron shell and is smaller.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Additionally, the effective nuclear charge has increased, and thus the electrons are attracted more strongly towards the nucleus and the ionic radius decreases.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The first ionisation energy of an element or molecule is the energy required to move the most loosely held electron from one mole of gaseous atoms of the element or molecules to form one mole of gaseous ions with electric charge +1.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The factors affecting the first ionisation energy are the nuclear charge, the amount of shielding by the inner electrons and the distance from the most loosely held electron from the nucleus, which is always an outer electron in main group elements.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The first two factors change the effective nuclear charge the most loosely held electron feels.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Since the outermost electron of alkali metals always feels the same effective nuclear charge (+1), the only factor which affects the first ionisation energy is the distance from the outermost electron to the nucleus.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Since this distance increases down the group, the outermost electron feels less attraction from the nucleus and thus the first ionisation energy decreases.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] This trend is broken in francium due to the relativistic stabilisation and contraction of the 7s orbital, bringing francium's valence electron closer to the nucleus than would be expected from non-relativistic calculations.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] This makes francium's outermost electron feel more attraction from the nucleus, increasing its first ionisation energy slightly beyond that of caesium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The second ionisation energy of the alkali metals is much higher than the first as the second-most loosely held electron is part of a fully filled electron shell and is thus difficult to remove.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The reactivities of the alkali metals increase going down the group.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] This is the result of a combination of two factors: the first ionisation energies and atomisation energies of the alkali metals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Because the first ionisation energy of the alkali metals decreases down the group, it is easier for the outermost electron to be removed from the atom and participate in chemical reactions, thus increasing reactivity down the group.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Adding the atomisation and first ionisation energies gives a quantity closely related to (but not equal to) the activation energy of the reaction of an alkali metal with another substance.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] This quantity decreases going down the group, and so does the activation energy; thus, chemical reactions can occur faster and the reactivity increases down the group.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Electronegativity is a chemical property that describes the tendency of an atom or a functional group to attract electrons (or electron density) towards itself.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] If the bond between sodium and chlorine in sodium chloride were covalent, the pair of shared electrons would be attracted to the chlorine because the effective nuclear charge on the outer electrons is +7 in chlorine but is only +1 in sodium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The electron pair is attracted so close to the chlorine atom that they are practically transferred to the chlorine atom (an ionic bond).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] However, if the sodium atom was replaced by a lithium atom, the electrons will not be attracted as close to the chlorine atom as before because the lithium atom is smaller, making the electron pair more strongly attracted to the closer effective nuclear charge from lithium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Hence, the larger alkali metal atoms (further down the group) will be less electronegative as the bonding pair is less strongly attracted towards them.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] As mentioned previously, francium is expected to be an exception.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Because of the higher electronegativity of lithium, some of its compounds have a more covalent character.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] For example, lithium iodide (LiI) will dissolve in organic solvents, a property of most covalent compounds.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Lithium fluoride (LiF) is the only alkali halide that is not soluble in water, and lithium hydroxide (LiOH) is the only alkali metal hydroxide that is not deliquescent.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The melting point of a substance is the point where it changes state from solid to liquid while the boiling point of a substance (in liquid state) is the point where the vapour pressure of the liquid equals the environmental pressure surrounding the liquid and all the liquid changes state to gas.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] As a metal is heated to its melting point, the metallic bonds keeping the atoms in place weaken so that the atoms can move around, and the metallic bonds eventually break completely at the metal's boiling point.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Therefore, the falling melting and boiling points of the alkali metals indicate that the strength of the metallic bonds of the alkali metals decreases down the group.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] This is because metal atoms are held together by the electromagnetic attraction from the positive ions to the delocalised electrons.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The increased nuclear charge is not a relevant factor due to the shielding effect.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The alkali metals all have the same crystal structure (body-centred cubic) and thus the only relevant factors are the number of atoms that can fit into a certain volume and the mass of one of the atoms, since density is defined as mass per unit volume.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The first factor depends on the volume of the atom and thus the atomic radius, which increases going down the group; thus, the volume of an alkali metal atom increases going down the group.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The mass of an alkali metal atom also increases going down the group.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Thus, the trend for the densities of the alkali metals depends on their atomic weights and atomic radii; if figures for these two factors are known, the ratios between the densities of the alkali metals can then be calculated.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] The resultant trend is that the densities of the alkali metals increase down the table, with an exception at potassium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Due to having the lowest atomic weight and the largest atomic radius of all the elements in their periods, the alkali metals are the least dense metals in the periodic table.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p01] Lithium, sodium, and potassium are the only three metals in the periodic table that are less dense than water: in fact, lithium is the least dense known solid at room temperature.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals form complete series of compounds with all usually encountered anions, which well illustrate group trends.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] These compounds can be described as involving the alkali metals losing electrons to acceptor species and forming monopositive ions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] This description is most accurate for alkali halides and becomes less and less accurate as cationic and anionic charge increase, and as the anion becomes larger and more polarisable.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] For instance, ionic bonding gives way to metallic bonding along the series NaCl, Na2O, Na2S, Na3P, Na3As, Na3Sb, Na3Bi, Na.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] All the alkali metals react vigorously or explosively with cold water, producing an aqueous solution of a strongly basic alkali metal hydroxide and releasing hydrogen gas.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] This reaction becomes more vigorous going down the group: lithium reacts steadily with effervescence, but sodium and potassium can ignite, and rubidium and caesium sink in water and generate hydrogen gas so rapidly that shock waves form in the water that may shatter glass containers.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] When an alkali metal is dropped into water, it produces an explosion, of which there are two separate stages.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The metal reacts with the water first, breaking the hydrogen bonds in the water and producing hydrogen gas; this takes place faster for the more reactive heavier alkali metals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Second, the heat generated by the first part of the reaction often ignites the hydrogen gas, causing it to burn explosively into the surrounding air.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] This secondary hydrogen gas explosion produces the visible flame above the bowl of water, lake or other body of water, not the initial reaction of the metal with water (which tends to happen mostly under water).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metal hydroxides are the most basic known hydroxides.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Recent research has suggested that the explosive behavior of alkali metals in water is driven by a Coulomb explosion rather than solely by rapid generation of hydrogen itself.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] All alkali metals melt as a part of the reaction with water.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Water molecules ionise the bare metallic surface of the liquid metal, leaving a positively charged metal surface and negatively charged water ions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The attraction between the charged metal and water ions will rapidly increase the surface area, causing an exponential increase of ionisation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] When the repulsive forces within the liquid metal surface exceeds the forces of the surface tension, it vigorously explodes.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The hydroxides themselves are the most basic hydroxides known, reacting with acids to give salts and with alcohols to give oligomeric alkoxides.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] They easily react with carbon dioxide to form carbonates or bicarbonates, or with hydrogen sulfide to form sulfides or bisulfides, and may be used to separate thiols from petroleum.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] They react with amphoteric oxides: for example, the oxides of aluminium, zinc, tin, and lead react with the alkali metal hydroxides to give aluminates, zincates, stannates, and plumbates.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Silicon dioxide is acidic, and thus the alkali metal hydroxides can also attack silicate glass.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals form many intermetallic compounds with each other and the elements from groups 2 to 13 in the periodic table of varying stoichiometries, such as the sodium amalgams with mercury, including Na5Hg8 and Na3Hg.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Some of these have ionic characteristics: taking the alloys with gold, the most electronegative of metals, as an example, NaAu and KAu are metallic, but RbAu and CsAu are semiconductors.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] NaK is an alloy of sodium and potassium that is very useful because it is liquid at room temperature, although precautions must be taken due to its extreme reactivity towards water and air.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] An alloy of 41% caesium, 47% sodium, and 12% potassium has the lowest known melting point of any metal or alloy, −78 °C.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Nevertheless, while the elements in group 14 and beyond tend to form discrete anionic clusters, group 13 elements tend to form polymeric ions with the alkali metal cations located between the giant ionic lattice.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] For example, NaTl consists of a polymeric anion (—Tl−—)n with a covalent diamond cubic structure with Na+ ions located between the anionic lattice.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The larger alkali metals cannot fit similarly into an anionic lattice and tend to force the heavier group 13 elements to form anionic clusters.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Boron is a special case, being the only nonmetal in group 13.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metal borides tend to be boron-rich, involving appreciable boron–boron bonding involving deltahedral structures, and are thermally unstable due to the alkali metals having a very high vapour pressure at elevated temperatures.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] This makes direct synthesis problematic because the alkali metals do not react with boron below 700 °C, and thus this must be accomplished in sealed containers with the alkali metal in excess.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Furthermore, exceptionally in this group, reactivity with boron decreases down the group: lithium reacts completely at 700 °C, but sodium at 900 °C and potassium not until 1200 °C, and the reaction is instantaneous for lithium but takes hours for potassium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Rubidium and caesium borides have not even been characterised.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Various phases are known, such as LiB10, NaB6, NaB15, and KB6.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Under high pressure the boron–boron bonding in the lithium borides changes from following Wade's rules to forming Zintl anions like the rest of group 13.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Lithium and sodium react with carbon to form acetylides, Li2C2 and Na2C2, which can also be obtained by reaction of the metal with acetylene.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] These compounds are over 200 times more electrically conductive than pure graphite, suggesting that the valence electron of the alkali metal is transferred to the graphite layers (e.g.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Upon heating of KC8, the elimination of potassium atoms results in the conversion in sequence to KC24, KC36, KC48 and finally KC60.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] KC8 is a very strong reducing agent and is pyrophoric and explodes on contact with water.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] While the larger alkali metals (K, Rb, and Cs) initially form MC8, the smaller ones initially form MC6, and indeed they require reaction of the metals with graphite at high temperatures around 500 °C to form.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Apart from this, the alkali metals are such strong reducing agents that they can even reduce buckminsterfullerene to produce solid fullerides M*n*C60; sodium, potassium, rubidium, and caesium can form fullerides where *n* = 2, 3, 4, or 6, and rubidium and caesium additionally can achieve *n* = 1.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] When the alkali metals react with the heavier elements in the carbon group (silicon, germanium, tin, and lead), ionic substances with cage-like structures are formed, such as the silicides M4Si4 (M = K, Rb, or Cs), which contains M+ and tetrahedral Si4−4 ions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The chemistry of alkali metal germanides, involving the germanide ion Ge4− and other cluster (Zintl) ions such as Ge2−4, Ge4−9, Ge2−9, and [(Ge9)2]6−, is largely analogous to that of the corresponding silicides.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Alkali metal stannides are mostly ionic, sometimes with the stannide ion (Sn4−), and sometimes with more complex Zintl ions such as Sn4−9, which appears in tetrapotassium nonastannide (K4Sn9).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The monatomic plumbide ion (Pb4−) is unknown, and indeed its formation is predicted to be energetically unfavourable; alkali metal plumbides have complex Zintl ions, such as Pb4−9.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] These alkali metal germanides, stannides, and plumbides may be produced by reducing germanium, tin, and lead with sodium metal in liquid ammonia.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Lithium, the lightest of the alkali metals, is the only alkali metal which reacts with nitrogen at standard conditions, and its nitride is the only stable alkali metal nitride.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Nitrogen is an unreactive gas because breaking the strong triple bond in the dinitrogen molecule (N2) requires a lot of energy.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The reactions of the other alkali metals with nitrogen would not release enough lattice energy and would thus be endothermic, so they do not form nitrides at standard conditions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Sodium nitride (Na3N) and potassium nitride (K3N), while existing, are extremely unstable, being prone to decomposing back into their constituent elements, and cannot be produced by reacting the elements with each other at standard conditions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Steric hindrance forbids the existence of rubidium or caesium nitride.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] However, sodium and potassium form colourless azide salts involving the linear N−3 anion; due to the large size of the alkali metal cations, they are thermally stable enough to be able to melt before decomposing.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] All the alkali metals react readily with phosphorus and arsenic to form phosphides and arsenides with the formula M3Pn (where M represents an alkali metal and Pn represents a pnictogen – phosphorus, arsenic, antimony, or bismuth).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] This is due to the greater size of the P3− and As3− ions, so that less lattice energy needs to be released for the salts to form.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] These are not the only phosphides and arsenides of the alkali metals: for example, potassium has nine different known phosphides, with formulae K3P, K4P3, K5P4, KP, K4P6, K3P7, K3P11, KP10.3, and KP15.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] While most metals form arsenides, only the alkali and alkaline earth metals form mostly ionic arsenides.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The structure of Na3As is complex with unusually short Na–Na distances of 328–330 pm which are shorter than in sodium metal, and this indicates that even with these electropositive metals the bonding cannot be straightforwardly ionic.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Other alkali metal arsenides not conforming to the formula M3As are known, such as LiAs, which has a metallic lustre and electrical conductivity indicating the presence of some metallic bonding.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The antimonides are unstable and reactive as the Sb3− ion is a strong reducing agent; reaction of them with acids form the toxic and unstable gas stibine (SbH3).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Indeed, they have some metallic properties, and the alkali metal antimonides of stoichiometry MSb involve antimony atoms bonded in a spiral Zintl structure.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Bismuthides are not even wholly ionic; they are intermetallic compounds containing partially metallic and partially ionic bonds.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] cluster, composed of three regular octahedra where each octahedron is connected to both of the others by one face each.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] All three octahedra have one edge in common.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] All the alkali metals react vigorously with oxygen at standard conditions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] They form various types of oxides, such as simple oxides (containing the O2− ion), peroxides (containing the O2−2 ion, where there is a single bond between the two oxygen atoms), superoxides (containing the O−2 ion), and many others.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Lithium burns in air to form lithium oxide, but sodium reacts with oxygen to form a mixture of sodium oxide and sodium peroxide.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Potassium forms a mixture of potassium peroxide and potassium superoxide, while rubidium and caesium form the superoxide exclusively.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Their reactivity increases going down the group: while lithium, sodium and potassium merely burn in air, rubidium and caesium are pyrophoric (spontaneously catch fire in air).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The smaller alkali metals tend to polarise the larger anions (the peroxide and superoxide) due to their small size.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] This attracts the electrons in the more complex anions towards one of its constituent oxygen atoms, forming an oxide ion and an oxygen atom.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] This causes lithium to form the oxide exclusively on reaction with oxygen at room temperature.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] This effect becomes drastically weaker for the larger sodium and potassium, allowing them to form the less stable peroxides.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Rubidium and caesium, at the bottom of the group, are so large that even the least stable superoxides can form.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Because the superoxide releases the most energy when formed, the superoxide is preferentially formed for the larger alkali metals where the more complex anions are not polarised.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The oxides and peroxides for these alkali metals do exist, but do not form upon direct reaction of the metal with oxygen at standard conditions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] In addition, the small size of the Li+ and O2− ions contributes to their forming a stable ionic lattice structure.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Under controlled conditions, however, all the alkali metals, with the exception of francium, are known to form their oxides, peroxides, and superoxides.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metal peroxides and superoxides are powerful oxidising agents.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] All the stable alkali metals except lithium can form red ozonides (MO3) through low-temperature reaction of the powdered anhydrous hydroxide with ozone: the ozonides may be then extracted using liquid ammonia.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] They slowly decompose at standard conditions to the superoxides and oxygen, and hydrolyse immediately to the hydroxides when in contact with water.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Potassium, rubidium, and caesium also form sesquioxides M2O3, which may be better considered peroxide disuperoxides, [(M+)4(O2−2)(O−2)2].
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Rubidium and caesium can form a great variety of suboxides with the metals in formal oxidation states below +1.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Rubidium can form Rb6O and Rb9O2 (copper-coloured) upon oxidation in air, while caesium forms an immense variety of oxides, such as the ozonide CsO3 and several brightly coloured suboxides, such as Cs7O (bronze), Cs4O (red-violet), Cs11O3 (violet), Cs3O (dark green), CsO, Cs3O2, as well as Cs7O2.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The last of these may be heated under vacuum to generate Cs2O.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals can also react analogously with the heavier chalcogens (sulfur, selenium, tellurium, and polonium), and all the alkali metal chalcogenides are known (with the exception of francium's).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Reaction with an excess of the chalcogen can similarly result in lower chalcogenides, with chalcogen ions containing chains of the chalcogen atoms in question.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] For example, sodium can react with sulfur to form the sulfide (Na2S) and various polysulfides with the formula Na2S*x* (*x* from 2 to 6), containing the S2− *x* ions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Due to the basicity of the Se2− and Te2− ions, the alkali metal selenides and tellurides are alkaline in solution; when reacted directly with selenium and tellurium, alkali metal polyselenides and polytellurides are formed along with the selenides and tellurides with the Se2− *x* and Te2− *x* ions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] They may be obtained directly from the elements in liquid ammonia or when air is not present, and are colourless, water-soluble compounds that air oxidises quickly back to selenium or tellurium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metal polonides are all ionic compounds containing the Po2− ion; they are very chemically stable and can be produced by direct reaction of the elements at around 300–400 °C.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals are among the most electropositive elements on the periodic table and thus tend to bond ionically to the most electronegative elements on the periodic table, the halogens (fluorine, chlorine, bromine, iodine, and astatine), forming salts known as the alkali metal halides.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The reaction is very vigorous and can sometimes result in explosions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] All twenty stable alkali metal halides are known; the unstable ones are not known, with the exception of sodium astatide, because of the great instability and rarity of astatine and francium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The most well-known of the twenty is certainly sodium chloride, otherwise known as common salt.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] All of the stable alkali metal halides have the formula MX where M is an alkali metal and X is a halogen.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] They are all white ionic crystalline solids that have high melting points.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] All the alkali metal halides are soluble in water except for lithium fluoride (LiF), which is insoluble in water due to its very high lattice enthalpy.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The high lattice enthalpy of lithium fluoride is due to the small sizes of the Li+ and F− ions, causing the electrostatic interactions between them to be strong: a similar effect occurs for magnesium fluoride, consistent with the diagonal relationship between lithium and magnesium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals also react similarly with hydrogen to form ionic alkali metal hydrides, where the hydride anion acts as a pseudohalide: these are often used as reducing agents, producing hydrides, complex metal hydrides, or hydrogen gas.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Other pseudohalides are also known, notably the cyanides.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] These are isostructural to the respective halides except for lithium cyanide, indicating that the cyanide ions may rotate freely.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Ternary alkali metal halide oxides, such as Na3ClO, K3BrO (yellow), Na4Br2O, Na4I2O, and K4Br2O, are also known.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The polyhalides are rather unstable, although those of rubidium and caesium are greatly stabilised by the feeble polarising power of these extremely large cations.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] encapsulating a potassium cation (purple).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] At crystalline state, obtained with an X-ray diffraction.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Alkali metal cations do not usually form coordination complexes with simple Lewis bases due to their low charge of just +1 and their relatively large size; thus the Li+ ion forms most complexes and the heavier alkali metal ions form less and less (though exceptions occur for weak complexes).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Lithium in particular has a very rich coordination chemistry in which it exhibits coordination numbers from 1 to 12, although octahedral hexacoordination is its preferred mode.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Because of this, anhydrous salts containing alkali metal cations are often used as desiccants.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Alkali metals also readily form complexes with crown ethers (e.g.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] 12-crown-4 for Li+, 15-crown-5 for Na+, 18-crown-6 for K+, and 21-crown-7 for Rb+) and cryptands due to electrostatic attraction.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The process may be speeded up by a catalyst.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Similar solutions are formed by the heavy divalent alkaline earth metals calcium, strontium, barium, as well as the divalent lanthanides, europium and ytterbium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The amide salt is quite insoluble and readily precipitates out of solution, leaving intensely coloured ammonia solutions of the alkali metals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Kraus identified the colour as being due to the presence of solvated electrons, which contribute to the high electrical conductivity of these solutions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] At low concentrations (below 3 M), the solution is dark blue and has ten times the conductivity of aqueous sodium chloride; at higher concentrations (above 3 M), the solution is copper-coloured and has approximately the conductivity of liquid metals like mercury.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] In addition to the alkali metal amide salt and solvated electrons, such ammonia solutions also contain the alkali metal cation (M+), the neutral alkali metal atom (M), diatomic alkali metal molecules (M2) and alkali metal anions (M−).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] These are unstable and eventually become the more thermodynamically stable alkali metal amide and hydrogen gas.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Solvated electrons are powerful reducing agents and are often used in chemical synthesis.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Being the smallest alkali metal, lithium forms the widest variety of and most stable organometallic compounds, which are bonded covalently.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Organolithium compounds are electrically non-conducting volatile solids or liquids that melt at low temperatures, and tend to form oligomers with the structure (RLi)*x* where R is the organic group.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] As the electropositive nature of lithium puts most of the charge density of the bond on the carbon atom, effectively creating a carbanion, organolithium compounds are extremely powerful bases and nucleophiles.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] For use as bases, butyllithiums are often used and are commercially available.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] An example of an organolithium compound is methyllithium ((CH3Li)*x*), which exists in tetrameric (*x* = 4, tetrahedral) and hexameric (*x* = 6, octahedral) forms.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Organolithium compounds, especially *n*-butyllithium, are useful reagents in organic synthesis, as might be expected given lithium's diagonal relationship with magnesium, which plays an important role in the Grignard reaction.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] For example, alkyllithiums and aryllithiums may be used to synthesise aldehydes and ketones by reaction with metal carbonyls.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The reaction with nickel tetracarbonyl, for example, proceeds through an unstable acyl nickel carbonyl complex which then undergoes electrophilic substitution to give the desired aldehyde (using H+ as the electrophile) or ketone (using an alkyl halide) product.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Alkyllithiums and aryllithiums may also react with *N*,*N*-disubstituted amides to give aldehydes and ketones, and symmetrical ketones by reacting with carbon monoxide.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] They thermally decompose to eliminate a β-hydrogen, producing alkenes and lithium hydride: another route is the reaction of ethers with alkyl- and aryllithiums that act as strong bases.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] In non-polar solvents, aryllithiums react as the carbanions they effectively are, turning carbon dioxide to aromatic carboxylic acids (ArCO2H) and aryl ketones to tertiary carbinols (Ar'2C(Ar)OH).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Finally, they may be used to synthesise other organometallic compounds through metal-halogen exchange.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Unlike the organolithium compounds, the organometallic compounds of the heavier alkali metals are predominantly ionic.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The application of organosodium compounds in chemistry is limited in part due to competition from organolithium compounds, which are commercially available and exhibit more convenient reactivity.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The principal organosodium compound of commercial importance is sodium cyclopentadienide.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Sodium tetraphenylborate can also be classified as an organosodium compound since in the solid state sodium is bound to the aryl groups.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Organometallic compounds of the higher alkali metals are even more reactive than organosodium compounds and of limited utility.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] A notable reagent is Schlosser's base, a mixture of *n*-butyllithium and potassium *tert*-butoxide.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] This reagent reacts with propene to form the compound allylpotassium (KCH2CHCH2).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] *cis*-2-Butene and *trans*-2-butene equilibrate when in contact with alkali metals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Whereas isomerisation is fast with lithium and sodium, it is slow with the heavier alkali metals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The heavier alkali metals also favour the sterically congested conformation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Several crystal structures of organopotassium compounds have been reported, establishing that they, like the sodium compounds, are polymeric.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Organosodium, organopotassium, organorubidium and organocaesium compounds are all mostly ionic and are insoluble (or nearly so) in nonpolar solvents.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Alkyl and aryl derivatives of sodium and potassium tend to react with air.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] They cause the cleavage of ethers, generating alkoxides.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] As such, they have to be made by reacting alkylmercury compounds with sodium or potassium metal in inert hydrocarbon solvents.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] While methylsodium forms tetramers like methyllithium, methylpotassium is more ionic and has the nickel arsenide structure with discrete methyl anions and potassium cations.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals and their hydrides react with acidic hydrocarbons, for example cyclopentadienes and terminal alkynes, to give salts.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Liquid ammonia, ether, or hydrocarbon solvents are used, the most common of which being tetrahydrofuran.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The most important of these compounds is sodium cyclopentadienide, NaC5H5, an important precursor to many transition metal cyclopentadienyl derivatives.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Similarly, the alkali metals react with cyclooctatetraene in tetrahydrofuran to give alkali metal cyclooctatetraenides; for example, dipotassium cyclooctatetraenide (K2C8H8) is an important precursor to many metal cyclooctatetraenyl derivatives, such as uranocene.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The large and very weakly polarising alkali metal cations can stabilise large, aromatic, polarisable radical anions, such as the dark-green sodium naphthalenide, Na+[C10H8•]−, a strong reducing agent.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Upon reacting with oxygen, alkali metals form oxides, peroxides, superoxides and suboxides.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] However, the first three are more common.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The table below shows the types of compounds formed in reaction with oxygen.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The compound in brackets represents the minor product of combustion.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metal peroxides are ionic compounds that are unstable in water.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The peroxide anion is weakly bound to the cation, and it is hydrolysed, forming stronger covalent bonds.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The other oxygen compounds are also unstable in water.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] With sulfur, they form sulfides and polysulfides.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Because alkali metal sulfides are essentially salts of a weak acid and a strong base, they form basic solutions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Lithium is the only metal that combines directly with nitrogen at room temperature.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Li3N can react with water to liberate ammonia.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] With hydrogen, alkali metals form saline hydrides that hydrolyse in water.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Lithium is the only metal that reacts directly with carbon to give dilithium acetylide.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Na and K can react with acetylene to give acetylides.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] On reaction with water, they generate hydroxide ions and hydrogen gas.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] This reaction is vigorous and highly exothermic and the hydrogen resulted may ignite in air or even explode in the case of Rb and Cs.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The alkali metals are very good reducing agents.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] They can reduce metal cations that are less electropositive.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Titanium is produced industrially by the reduction of titanium tetrachloride with Na at 400 °C (van Arkel–de Boer process).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Alkali metals react with halogen derivatives to generate hydrocarbon via the Wurtz reaction.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Alkali metals dissolve in liquid ammonia or other donor solvents like aliphatic amines or hexamethylphosphoramide to give blue solutions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] These solutions are believed to contain free electrons.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Due to the presence of solvated electrons, these solutions are very powerful reducing agents used in organic synthesis.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Reaction 1) is known as Birch reduction.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Although francium is the heaviest alkali metal that has been discovered, there has been some theoretical work predicting the physical and chemical characteristics of hypothetical heavier alkali metals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Being the first period 8 element, the undiscovered element ununennium (element 119) is predicted to be the next alkali metal after francium and behave much like their lighter congeners; however, it is also predicted to differ from the lighter alkali metals in some properties.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Its chemistry is predicted to be closer to that of potassium or rubidium instead of caesium or francium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] This is unusual as periodic trends, ignoring relativistic effects would predict ununennium to be even more reactive than caesium and francium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] This lowered reactivity is due to the relativistic stabilisation of ununennium's valence electron, increasing ununennium's first ionisation energy and decreasing the metallic and ionic radii; this effect is already seen for francium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] This assumes that ununennium will behave chemically as an alkali metal, which, although likely, may not be true due to relativistic effects.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The relativistic stabilisation of the 8s orbital also increases ununennium's electron affinity far beyond that of caesium and francium; indeed, ununennium is expected to have an electron affinity higher than all the alkali metals lighter than it.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Relativistic effects also cause a very large drop in the polarisability of ununennium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] On the other hand, ununennium is predicted to continue the trend of melting points decreasing going down the group, being expected to have a melting point between 0 °C and 30 °C.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] On the other hand, the ionic radius of the Uue+ ion is predicted to be larger than that of Rb+, because the 7p orbitals are destabilised and are thus larger than the p-orbitals of the lower shells.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Indeed, many ununennium compounds are expected to have a large covalent character, due to the involvement of the 7p3/2 electrons in the bonding.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Not as much work has been done predicting the properties of the alkali metals beyond ununennium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] This element would be intermediate in properties between an alkali metal and a group 11 element, and while its physical and atomic properties would be closer to the former, its chemistry may be closer to that of the latter.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] However, the 7d electrons of unhexpentium may also be able to participate in chemical reactions along with the 9s electron, possibly allowing oxidation states beyond +1, whence the likely transition metal behaviour of unhexpentium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Due to the alkali and alkaline earth metals both being s-block elements, these predictions for the trends and properties of ununennium and unhexpentium also mostly hold quite similarly for the corresponding alkaline earth metals unbinilium (Ubn) and unhexhexium (Uhh).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] The probable properties of further alkali metals beyond unsepttrium have not been explored yet as of 2019, and they may or may not be able to exist.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] In periods 8 and above of the periodic table, relativistic and shell-structure effects become so strong that extrapolations from lighter congeners become completely inaccurate.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p02] Interest in the chemical properties of ununennium, unhexpentium, and unsepttrium stems from the fact that they are located close to the expected locations of islands of stability, centered at elements 122 (306Ubb) and 164 (482Uhq).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Many other substances are similar to the alkali metals in their tendency to form monopositive cations.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Analogously to the pseudohalogens, they have sometimes been called "pseudo-alkali metals".
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] These substances include some elements and many more polyatomic ions; the polyatomic ions are especially similar to the alkali metals in their large size and weak polarising power.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The element hydrogen, with one electron per neutral atom, is usually placed at the top of Group 1 of the periodic table because of its electron configuration.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] But hydrogen is not normally considered to be an alkali metal.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Metallic hydrogen, which only exists at very high pressures, is known for its electrical and magnetic properties, not its chemical properties.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Under typical conditions, pure hydrogen exists as a diatomic gas consisting of two atoms per molecule (H2); however, the alkali metals form diatomic molecules (such as dilithium, Li2) only at high temperatures, when they are in the gaseous state.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Hydrogen, like the alkali metals, has one valence electron and reacts easily with the halogens, but the similarities mostly end there because of the small size of a bare proton H+ compared to the alkali metal cations.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Its placement above lithium is primarily due to its electron configuration.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] It is sometimes placed above fluorine due to their similar chemical properties, though the resemblance is likewise not absolute.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The first ionisation energy of hydrogen (1312.0 kJ/mol) is much higher than that of the alkali metals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] As only one additional electron is required to fill in the outermost shell of the hydrogen atom, hydrogen often behaves like a halogen, forming the negative hydride ion, and is very occasionally considered to be a halogen on that basis.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] (The alkali metals can also form negative ions, known as alkalides, but these are little more than laboratory curiosities, being unstable.) An argument against this placement is that formation of hydride from hydrogen is endothermic, unlike the exothermic formation of halides from halogens.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The radius of the H− anion also does not fit the trend of increasing size going down the halogens: indeed, H− is very diffuse because its single proton cannot easily control both electrons.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The electrical resistivity of liquid metallic hydrogen at 3000 K is approximately equal to that of liquid rubidium and caesium at 2000 K at the respective pressures when they undergo a nonmetal-to-metal transition.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The 1s1 electron configuration of hydrogen, while analogous to that of the alkali metals (ns1), is unique because there is no 1p subshell.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Hence it can lose an electron to form the hydron H+, or gain one to form the hydride ion H−.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] In the former case it resembles superficially the alkali metals; in the latter case, the halogens, but the differences due to the lack of a 1p subshell are important enough that neither group fits the properties of hydrogen well.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Group 14 is also a good fit in terms of thermodynamic properties such as ionisation energy and electron affinity, but hydrogen cannot be tetravalent.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Indeed, transferring of protons between chemicals is the basis of acid-base chemistry.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Also unique is hydrogen's ability to form hydrogen bonds, which are an effect of charge-transfer, electrostatic, and electron correlative contributing phenomena.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] While analogous lithium bonds are also known, they are mostly electrostatic.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Nevertheless, hydrogen can take on the same structural role as the alkali metals in some molecular crystals, and has a close relationship with the lightest alkali metals (especially lithium).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The ammonium ion (NH+4) has very similar properties to the heavier alkali metals, acting as an alkali metal intermediate between potassium and rubidium, and is often considered a close relative.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] For example, most alkali metal salts are soluble in water, a property which ammonium salts share.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] It has been estimated that the transition from a mixture of ammonia and dihydrogen molecules to metallic ammonium may occur at pressures just below 25 GPa.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Under standard conditions, ammonium can form a metallic amalgam with mercury.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Other "pseudo-alkali metals" include the alkylammonium cations, in which some of the hydrogen atoms in the ammonium cation are replaced by alkyl or aryl groups.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] In particular, the quaternary ammonium cations (NR+4) are very useful since they are permanently charged, and they are often used as an alternative to the expensive Cs+ to stabilise very large and very easily polarisable anions such as HI−2.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Tetraalkylammonium hydroxides, like alkali metal hydroxides, are very strong bases that react with atmospheric carbon dioxide to form carbonates.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Cobaltocene, Co(C5H5)2, is a metallocene, the cobalt analogue of ferrocene.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Cobaltocene has 19 valence electrons, one more than usually found in organotransition metal complexes, such as its very stable relative, ferrocene, in accordance with the 18-electron rule.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] This additional electron occupies an orbital that is antibonding with respect to the Co–C bonds.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Consequently, many chemical reactions of Co(C5H5)2 are characterized by its tendency to lose this "extra" electron, yielding a very stable 18-electron cation known as cobaltocenium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Many cobaltocenium salts coprecipitate with caesium salts, and cobaltocenium hydroxide is a strong base that absorbs atmospheric carbon dioxide to form cobaltocenium carbonate.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Like the alkali metals, cobaltocene is a strong reducing agent, and decamethylcobaltocene is stronger still due to the combined inductive effect of the ten methyl groups.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Cobalt may be substituted by its heavier congener rhodium to give rhodocene, an even stronger reducing agent.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Iridocene (involving iridium) would presumably be still more potent, but is not very well-studied due to its instability.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Thallium is the heaviest stable element in group 13 of the periodic table.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] It was sometimes considered an alkali metal in continental Europe (but not in England) in the years immediately following its discovery, and was placed just after caesium as the sixth alkali metal in Dmitri Mendeleev's 1869 periodic table and Julius Lothar Meyer's 1868 periodic table.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Mendeleev's 1871 periodic table and Meyer's 1870 periodic table put thallium in its current position in the boron group and left the space below caesium blank.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] However, thallium also displays the oxidation state +3, which no known alkali metal displays (although ununennium, the undiscovered seventh alkali metal, is predicted to possibly display the +3 oxidation state).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The sixth alkali metal is now considered to be francium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] While Tl+ is stabilised by the inert-pair effect, this inert pair of 6s electrons is still able to participate chemically, so that these electrons are stereochemically active in aqueous solution.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Additionally, the thallium halides (except TlF) are quite insoluble in water, and TlI has an unusual structure because of the presence of the stereochemically active inert pair in thallium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The group 11 metals (or coinage metals), copper, silver, and gold, are typically categorised as transition metals given they can form ions with incomplete d-shells.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Physically, they have the relatively low melting points and high electronegativity values associated with post-transition metals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] "The filled *d* subshell and free *s* electron of Cu, Ag, and Au contribute to their high electrical and thermal conductivity.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] They are occasionally classified as post-transition metals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Their spectra are analogous to those of the alkali metals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Their monopositive ions are paramagnetic and contribute no colour to their salts, like those of the alkali metals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] In Mendeleev's 1871 periodic table, copper, silver, and gold are listed twice, once under group VIII (with the iron triad and platinum group metals), and once under group IB.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Group IB was nonetheless parenthesised to note that it was tentative.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Mendeleev's main criterion for group assignment was the maximum oxidation state of an element: on that basis, the group 11 elements could not be classified in group IB, due to the existence of copper(II) and gold(III) compounds being known at that time.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] However, eliminating group IB would make group I the only main group (group VIII was labelled a transition group) to lack an A–B bifurcation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The coinage metals were traditionally regarded as a subdivision of the alkali metal group, due to them sharing the characteristic s1 electron configuration of the alkali metals (group 1: p6s1; group 11: d10s1).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] However, the similarities are largely confined to the stoichiometries of the +1 compounds of both groups, and not their chemical properties.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] This stems from the filled d subshell providing a much weaker shielding effect on the outermost s electron than the filled p subshell, so that the coinage metals have much higher first ionisation energies and smaller ionic radii than do the corresponding alkali metals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Furthermore, they have higher melting points, hardnesses, and densities, and lower reactivities and solubilities in liquid ammonia, as well as having more covalent character in their compounds.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Finally, the alkali metals are at the top of the electrochemical series, whereas the coinage metals are almost at the very bottom.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The production of pure alkali metals is somewhat complicated due to their extreme reactivity with commonly used substances, such as water.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The remaining insoluble alkali metal carbonate is then precipitated selectively; the salt is then dissolved in hydrochloric acid to produce the chloride.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The result is then left to evaporate and the alkali metal can then be isolated.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium and sodium are typically isolated through electrolysis from their liquid chlorides, with calcium chloride typically added to lower the melting point of the mixture.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The heavier alkali metals, however, are more typically isolated in a different way, where a reducing agent (typically sodium for potassium and magnesium or calcium for the heaviest alkali metals) is used to reduce the alkali metal chloride.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The liquid or gaseous product (the alkali metal) then undergoes fractional distillation for purification.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Most routes to the pure alkali metals require the use of electrolysis due to their high reactivity; one of the few which does not is the pyrolysis of the corresponding alkali metal azide, which yields the metal for sodium, potassium, rubidium, and caesium and the nitride for lithium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium salts have to be extracted from the water of mineral springs, brine pools, and brine deposits.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The metal is produced electrolytically from a mixture of fused lithium chloride and potassium chloride.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium occurs mostly in seawater and dried seabed, but is now produced through electrolysis of sodium chloride by lowering the melting point of the substance to below 700 °C through the use of a Downs cell.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Extremely pure sodium can be produced through the thermal decomposition of sodium azide.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium occurs in many minerals, such as sylvite (potassium chloride).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Previously, potassium was generally made from the electrolysis of potassium chloride or potassium hydroxide, found extensively in places such as Canada, Russia, Belarus, Germany, Israel, United States, and Jordan, in a method similar to how sodium was produced in the late 1800s and early 1900s.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] However, these methods are problematic because the potassium metal tends to dissolve in its molten chloride and vaporises significantly at the operating temperatures, potentially forming the explosive superoxide.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] As a result, pure potassium metal is now produced by reducing molten potassium chloride with sodium metal at 850 °C.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Although sodium is less reactive than potassium, this process works because at such high temperatures potassium is more volatile than sodium and can easily be distilled off, so that the equilibrium shifts towards the right to produce more potassium gas and proceeds almost to completion.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Metals like sodium are obtained by electrolysis of molten salts.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Rb & Cs obtained mainly as by products of Li processing.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] To make pure caesium, ores of caesium and rubidium are crushed and heated to 650 °C with sodium metal, generating an alloy that can then be separated via a fractional distillation technique.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Because metallic caesium is too reactive to handle, it is normally offered as caesium azide (CsN3).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Caesium hydroxide is formed when caesium interacts aggressively with water and ice (CsOH).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium is the 16th most abundant element in the earth's crust; however, it is quite rare.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Some minerals found in North America, South Africa, Russia, and Canada contain rubidium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Some potassium minerals (lepidolites, biotites, feldspar, carnallite) contain it, together with caesium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Pollucite, carnallite, leucite, and lepidolite are all minerals that contain rubidium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] As a by-product of lithium extraction, it is commercially obtained from lepidolite.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium is also found in potassium rocks and brines, which is a commercial supply.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The majority of rubidium is now obtained as a byproduct of refining lithium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium is used in vacuum tubes as a getter, a material that combines with and removes trace gases from vacuum tubes.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] For several years in the 1950s and 1960s, a by-product of the potassium production called Alkarb was a main source for rubidium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Alkarb contained 21% rubidium while the rest was potassium and a small fraction of caesium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Today the largest producers of caesium, for example the Tanco Mine in Manitoba, Canada, produce rubidium as by-product from pollucite.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Today, a common method for separating rubidium from potassium and caesium is the fractional crystallisation of a rubidium and caesium alum (Cs, Rb)Al(SO4)2·12H2O, which yields pure rubidium alum after approximately 30 recrystallisations.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The limited applications and the lack of a mineral rich in rubidium limit the production of rubidium compounds to 2 to 4 tonnes per year.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Caesium, however, is not produced from the above reaction.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Instead, the mining of pollucite ore is the main method of obtaining pure caesium, extracted from the ore mainly by three methods: acid digestion, alkaline decomposition, and direct reduction.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Both metals are produced as by-products of lithium production: after 1958, when interest in lithium's thermonuclear properties increased sharply, the production of rubidium and caesium also increased correspondingly.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Pure rubidium and caesium metals are produced by reducing their chlorides with calcium metal at 750 °C and low pressure.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] As a result of its extreme rarity in nature, most francium is synthesised in the nuclear reaction 197Au + 18O → 210Fr + 5 n, yielding francium-209, francium-210, and francium-211.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The greatest quantity of francium ever assembled to date is about 300,000 neutral atoms, which were synthesised using the nuclear reaction given above.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] When the only natural isotope francium-223 is specifically required, it is produced as the alpha daughter of actinium-227, itself produced synthetically from the neutron irradiation of natural radium-226, one of the daughters of natural uranium-238.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium, sodium, and potassium have many useful applications, while rubidium and caesium are very notable in academic contexts but do not have many applications yet.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium is the key ingredient for a range of lithium-based batteries, and lithium oxide can help process silica.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium stearate is a thickener and can be used to make lubricating greases; it is produced from lithium hydroxide, which is also used to absorb carbon dioxide in space capsules and submarines.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium chloride is used as a brazing alloy for aluminium parts.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] In medicine, some lithium salts are used as mood-stabilising pharmaceuticals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Metallic lithium is used in alloys with magnesium and aluminium to give very tough and light alloys.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium compounds have many applications, the most well-known being sodium chloride as table salt.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium salts of fatty acids are used as soap.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Pure sodium metal also has many applications, including use in sodium-vapour lamps, which produce very efficient light compared to other types of lighting, and can help smooth the surface of other metals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Being a strong reducing agent, it is often used to reduce many other metals, such as titanium and zirconium, from their chlorides.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Furthermore, it is very useful as a heat-exchange liquid in fast breeder nuclear reactors due to its low melting point, viscosity, and cross-section towards neutron absorption.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium-ion batteries may provide cheaper alternatives to their equivalent lithium-based cells.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Both sodium and potassium are commonly used as GRAS counterions to create more water-soluble and hence more bioavailable salt forms of acidic pharmaceuticals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium compounds are often used as fertilisers as potassium is an important element for plant nutrition.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium hydroxide is a very strong base, and is used to control the pH of various substances.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium nitrate and potassium permanganate are often used as powerful oxidising agents.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium superoxide is used in breathing masks, as it reacts with carbon dioxide to give potassium carbonate and oxygen gas.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Pure potassium metal is not often used, but its alloys with sodium may substitute for pure sodium in fast breeder nuclear reactors.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium and caesium are often used in atomic clocks.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Caesium atomic clocks are extraordinarily accurate; if a clock had been made at the time of the dinosaurs, it would be off by less than four seconds (after 80 million years).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] For that reason, caesium atoms are used as the definition of the second.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium ions are often used in purple fireworks, and caesium is often used in drilling fluids in the petroleum industry.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Francium has no commercial applications, but because of francium's relatively simple atomic structure, among other things, it has been used in spectroscopy experiments, leading to more information regarding energy levels and the coupling constants of the weak interaction.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Studies on the light emitted by laser-trapped francium-210 ions have provided accurate data on transitions between atomic energy levels, similar to those predicted by quantum theory.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Pure alkali metals are dangerously reactive with air and water and must be kept away from heat, fire, oxidising agents, acids, most organic compounds, halocarbons, plastics, and moisture.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] They also react with carbon dioxide and carbon tetrachloride, so that normal fire extinguishers are counterproductive when used on alkali metal fires.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Some Class D dry powder extinguishers designed for metal fires are effective, depriving the fire of oxygen and cooling the alkali metal.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Experiments are usually conducted using only small quantities of a few grams in a fume hood.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Small quantities of lithium may be disposed of by reaction with cool water, but the heavier alkali metals should be dissolved in the less reactive isopropanol.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The alkali metals must be stored under mineral oil or an inert atmosphere.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The inert atmosphere used may be argon or nitrogen gas, except for lithium, which reacts with nitrogen.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The bioinorganic chemistry of the alkali metal ions has been extensively reviewed.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Solid state crystal structures have been determined for many complexes of alkali metal ions in small peptides, nucleic acid constituents, carbohydrates and ionophore complexes.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium naturally only occurs in traces in biological systems and has no known biological role, but does have effects on the body when ingested.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Lithium carbonate is used as a mood stabiliser in psychiatry to treat bipolar disorder (manic-depression) in daily doses of about 0.5 to 2 grams, although there are side-effects.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Excessive ingestion of lithium causes drowsiness, slurred speech and vomiting, among other symptoms, and poisons the central nervous system, which is dangerous as the required dosage of lithium to treat bipolar disorder is only slightly lower than the toxic dosage.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Its biochemistry, the way it is handled by the human body and studies using rats and goats suggest that it is an essential trace element, although the natural biological function of lithium in humans has yet to be identified.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium and potassium occur in all known biological systems, generally functioning as electrolytes inside and outside cells.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium is an essential nutrient that regulates blood volume, blood pressure, osmotic equilibrium and pH; the minimum physiological requirement for sodium is 500 milligrams per day.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Sodium chloride (also known as common salt) is the principal source of sodium in the diet, and is used as seasoning and preservative, such as for pickling and jerky; most of it comes from processed foods.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The Dietary Reference Intake for sodium is 1.5 grams per day, but most people in the United States consume more than 2.3 grams per day, the minimum amount that promotes hypertension; this in turn causes 7.6 million premature deaths worldwide.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium is the major cation (positive ion) inside animal cells, while sodium is the major cation outside animal cells.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The concentration differences of these charged particles causes a difference in electric potential between the inside and outside of cells, known as the membrane potential.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The balance between potassium and sodium is maintained by ion transporter proteins in the cell membrane.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The cell membrane potential created by potassium and sodium ions allows the cell to generate an action potential—a "spike" of electrical discharge.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The ability of cells to produce electrical discharge is critical for body functions such as neurotransmission, muscle contraction, and heart function.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Disruption of this balance may thus be fatal: for example, ingestion of large amounts of potassium compounds can lead to hyperkalemia strongly influencing the cardiovascular system.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Potassium chloride is used in the United States for lethal injection executions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Due to their similar atomic radii, rubidium and caesium in the body mimic potassium and are taken up similarly.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium has no known biological role, but may help stimulate metabolism, and, similarly to caesium, replace potassium in the body causing potassium deficiency.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Partial substitution is quite possible and rather non-toxic: a 70 kg person contains on average 0.36 g of rubidium, and an increase in this value by 50 to 100 times did not show negative effects in test persons.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Rats can survive up to 50% substitution of potassium by rubidium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Rubidium (and to a much lesser extent caesium) can function as temporary cures for hypokalemia; while rubidium can adequately physiologically substitute potassium in some systems, caesium is never able to do so.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] There is only very limited evidence in the form of deficiency symptoms for rubidium being possibly essential in goats; even if this is true, the trace amounts usually present in food are more than enough.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Caesium compounds are rarely encountered by most people, but most caesium compounds are mildly toxic.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Like rubidium, caesium tends to substitute potassium in the body, but is significantly larger and is therefore a poorer substitute.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Excess caesium can lead to hypokalemia, arrhythmia, and acute cardiac arrest, but such amounts would not ordinarily be encountered in natural sources.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] As such, caesium is not a major chemical environmental pollutant.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] The median lethal dose (LD50) value for caesium chloride in mice is 2.3 g per kilogram, which is comparable to the LD50 values of potassium chloride and sodium chloride.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Caesium chloride has been promoted as an alternative cancer therapy, but has been linked to the deaths of over 50 patients, on whom it was used as part of a scientifically unvalidated cancer treatment.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Radioisotopes of caesium require special precautions: the improper handling of caesium-137 gamma ray sources can lead to release of this radioisotope and radiation injuries.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Perhaps the best-known case is the Goiânia accident of 1987, in which an improperly-disposed-of radiation therapy system from an abandoned clinic in the city of Goiânia, Brazil, was scavenged from a junkyard, and the glowing caesium salt sold to curious, uneducated buyers.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] This led to four deaths and serious injuries from radiation exposure.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Together with caesium-134, iodine-131, and strontium-90, caesium-137 was among the isotopes distributed by the Chernobyl disaster which constitute the greatest risk to health.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali-metal-p03] Radioisotopes of francium would presumably be dangerous as well due to their high decay energy and short half-life, but none have been produced in large enough amounts to pose any serious risk.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] In chemistry, an **alkali** (/ˈælkəlaɪ/ ⓘ; from the Arabic word *al-qaly*, القالِي "saltwort") also **base** is a hydroxide of any of either the alkali metal which are Group I s-block elements, or the alkaline earth metal which are Group II s-block.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] *Alkali* can also be defined as a base that dissolves in water.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] A solution of a soluble base has a pH greater than 7.0.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] The adjectives ***alkaline*** and, less often, ***alkalescent*** are commonly used in English as a synonyms for *basic*, especially for bases soluble in water.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] This broad use of the term is likely to have come about because alkalis were the first bases known to obey the Arrhenius definition of a base, and they are still among the most common bases.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] The word *alkali* is derived from Arabic *al qalīy* (or *alkali*), meaning 'the calcined ashes' (see calcination), referring to the original source of alkaline substances.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] A water-extract of burned plant ashes, called *potash* and composed mostly of potassium carbonate, was mildly basic.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] After heating this substance with calcium hydroxide (*slaked lime*), a far more strongly basic substance known as *caustic potash* (potassium hydroxide) was produced.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] Caustic potash was traditionally used in conjunction with animal fats to produce soft soaps, one of the caustic processes that rendered soaps from fats in the process of saponification, one known since antiquity.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] Plant potash lent the name to the element potassium, which was first derived from caustic potash, and also gave potassium its chemical symbol **K** (from the German name *Kalium*), which ultimately derived from al**k**ali.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] Alkalis are all Arrhenius bases, ones which form hydroxide ions (OH−) when dissolved in water.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] The terms "base" and "alkali" are often used interchangeably, particularly outside the context of chemistry and chemical engineering.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] There are various, more specific definitions for the concept of an alkali.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] Alkalis are usually defined as a subset of the bases.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] The second subset of bases is also called an "Arrhenius base".
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] Soils with pH values that are higher than 7.3 are usually defined as being alkaline.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] These soils can occur naturally due to the presence of alkali salts.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] Although many plants do prefer slightly basic soil (including vegetables like cabbage and fodder like buffalo grass), most plants prefer mildly acidic soil (with pHs between 6.0 and 6.8), and alkaline soils can cause problems.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkali] In alkali lakes (also called *soda lakes*), evaporation concentrates the naturally occurring carbonate salts, giving rise to an alkalic and often saline lake.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The **alkaline earth metals** are six chemical elements in group 2 of the periodic table.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] They are beryllium (Be), magnesium (Mg), calcium (Ca), strontium (Sr), barium (Ba), and radium (Ra).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The elements have very similar properties: they are all shiny, silvery-white, somewhat reactive metals at standard temperature and pressure.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Together with helium, these elements have in common an outer s orbital which is full—that is, this orbital contains its full complement of two electrons, which the alkaline earth metals readily lose to form cations with charge +2, and an oxidation state of +2.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Helium is grouped with the noble gases and not with the alkaline earth metals, but it is theorized to have some similarities to beryllium when forced into bonding and has sometimes been suggested to belong to group 2.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] All the discovered alkaline earth metals occur in nature, although radium occurs only through the decay chain of uranium and thorium and not as a primordial element.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] There have been experiments, all unsuccessful, to try to synthesize element 120, the next potential member of the group.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The chemistry of radium is not well-established due to its radioactivity; thus, the presentation of its properties here is limited.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The alkaline earth metals are all silver-colored and soft, and have relatively low densities, melting points, and boiling points.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] In chemical terms, all of the alkaline earth metals react with the halogens to form the alkaline earth metal halides, all of which are ionic crystalline compounds (except for beryllium chloride, beryllium bromide and beryllium iodide, which are covalent).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] All the alkaline earth metals except beryllium also react with water to form strongly alkaline hydroxides and, thus, should be handled with great care.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The heavier alkaline earth metals react more vigorously than the lighter ones.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The alkaline earth metals have the second-lowest first ionization energies in their respective periods of the periodic table because of their somewhat low effective nuclear charges and the ability to attain a full outer shell configuration by losing just two electrons.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The second ionization energy of all of the alkaline metals is also somewhat low.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium is an exception: It does not react with water or steam unless at very high temperatures, and its halides are covalent.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] If beryllium did form compounds with an ionization state of +2, it would polarize electron clouds that are near it very strongly and would cause extensive orbital overlap, since beryllium has a high charge density.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] All compounds that include beryllium have a covalent bond.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Even the compound beryllium fluoride, which is the most ionic beryllium compound, has a low melting point and a low electrical conductivity when melted.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] All the alkaline earth metals have two electrons in their valence shell, so the energetically preferred state of achieving a filled electron shell is to lose two electrons to form doubly charged positive ions.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The alkaline earth metals all react with the halogens to form ionic halides, such as calcium chloride (CaCl 2), as well as reacting with oxygen to form oxides such as strontium oxide (SrO).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium, strontium, and barium react with water to produce hydrogen gas and their respective hydroxides (magnesium also reacts, but much more slowly), and also undergo transmetalation reactions to exchange ligands.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Isotopes of all six alkaline earth metals are present in the Earth's crust and the Solar System at varying concentrations, dependent upon the nuclides' half-lives and, hence, their nuclear stabilities.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The four underlined isotopes in the list are predicted by radionuclide decay energetics to be only observationally stable and to decay with extremely long half-lives through double-beta decay, though no decays attributed definitively to these isotopes have yet been observed as of 2024.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Radium has no stable nor primordial isotopes.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] In addition to the stable species, calcium and barium each have one extremely long-lived and primordial radionuclide: calcium-48 and barium-130, with half-lives of 5.6×1019 and 1.6×1021 years, respectively.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Both are far longer than the current age of the universe (4.7× and 117× billion times longer, respectively) and less than one part per ten billion has decayed since the formation of the Earth.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The two isotopes are stable for practical purposes.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Apart from the 21 stable or nearly-stable isotopes, the six alkaline earth elements each possess a large number of known radioisotopes.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium-7, beryllium-10, and calcium-41 are trace, as well as cosmogenic, nuclides, formed by the impact of cosmic rays with atmospheric or crustal atoms.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The longest half-lives among them are 1.387 million years for beryllium-10, 99.4 thousand years for calcium-41, 1599 years for radium-226 (radium's longest-lived isotope), 28.90 years for strontium-90, 10.51 years for barium-133, and 5.75 years for radium-228.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] All others have half-lives of less than half a year, most significantly shorter.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium-48 and barium-130, the two primordial and non-stable isotopes, decay only through double beta emission and have extremely long half-lives, by virtue of the extremely low probability of both beta decays occurring at the same time.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] All isotopes of radium are highly radioactive and are primarily generated through the decay of heavier radionuclides.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The longest-lived of them is radium-226, a member of the decay chain of uranium-238.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium-90 and barium-140 are common fission products of uranium in nuclear reactors, accounting for 5.73% and 6.31% of uranium-235's fission products respectively when bombarded by thermal neutrons.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The two isotopes have half-lives each of 28.90 years and 12.7 days.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium-90 is produced in appreciable quantities in operating nuclear reactors running on uranium-235 or plutonium-239 fuel, and a minuscule secular equilibrium concentration is also present due to rare spontaneous fission decays in naturally occurring uranium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium-48 is the lightest nuclide known to undergo double beta decay.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Naturally occurring calcium and barium are very weakly radioactive: calcium contains about 0.1874% calcium-48, and barium contains about 0.1062% barium-130.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] On average, one double-beta decay of calcium-48 will occur per second for every 90 tons of natural calcium, or 230 tons of limestone (calcium carbonate).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Through the same decay mechanism, one decay of barium-130 will occur per second for every 16,000 tons of natural barium, or 27,000 tons of baryte (barium sulfate).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The longest-lived isotope of radium is radium-226 with a half-life of 1600 years; it, along with radium-223, -224, and -228, occurs naturally in the decay chains of primordial thorium and uranium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium-8 is notable by its absence as it splits in half virtually instantaneously into two alpha particles whenever it is formed.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The triple alpha process in stars can only occur at energies high enough for beryllium-8 to fuse with a third alpha particle before it can decay, forming carbon-12.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] This thermonuclear rate-limiting bottleneck is the reason most main sequence stars spend billions of years fusing hydrogen within their cores, and only rarely manage to fuse carbon before collapsing into a stellar remnant, and even then merely for a timescale of ~1000 years.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The radioisotopes of alkaline earth metals tend to be "bone seekers" as they behave chemically similar to calcium, an integral component of hydroxyapatite in compact bone, and gradually accumulate in the human skeleton.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The incorporated radionuclides inflict significant damage to the bone marrow over time through the emission of ionizing radiation, primarily alpha particles.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] This property is made use of in a positive manner in the radiotherapy of certain bone cancers, since the radionuclides' chemical properties causes them to preferentially target cancerous growths in bone matter, leaving the rest of the body relatively unharmed.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Compared to their neighbors in the periodic table, alkaline earth metals tend to have a larger number of stable isotopes as they all possess an even number of protons, owing to their status as group 2 elements.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Their isotopes are generally more stable due to nucleon pairing.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] This stability is further enhanced if the isotope also has an even number of neutrons, as both kinds of nucleons can then participate in pairing and contribute to nuclei stability.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The alkaline earth metals are named after their oxides, the *alkaline earths*, whose old-fashioned names were beryllia, magnesia, lime, strontia, and baria.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] These oxides are basic (alkaline) when combined with water.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] "Earth" was a term applied by early chemists to nonmetallic substances that are insoluble in water and resistant to heating—properties shared by these oxides.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The realization that these earths were not elements but compounds is attributed to the chemist Antoine Lavoisier.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] In his *Traité Élémentaire de Chimie* (*Elements of Chemistry*) of 1789 he called them salt-forming earth elements.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Later, he suggested that the alkaline earths might be metal oxides, but admitted that this was mere conjecture.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] In 1808, acting on Lavoisier's idea, Humphry Davy became the first to obtain samples of the metals by electrolysis of their molten earths, thus supporting Lavoisier's hypothesis and causing the group to be named the *alkaline earth metals*.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The calcium compounds calcite and lime have been known and used since prehistoric times.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The same is true for the beryllium compounds beryl and emerald.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The other compounds of the alkaline earth metals were discovered starting in the early 15th century.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The magnesium compound magnesium sulfate was first discovered in 1618 by a farmer at Epsom in England.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium carbonate was discovered in minerals in the Scottish village of Strontian in 1790.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The last element is the least abundant: radioactive radium, which was extracted from uraninite in 1898.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] All elements except beryllium were isolated by electrolysis of molten compounds.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium, calcium, and strontium were first produced by Humphry Davy in 1808, whereas beryllium was independently isolated by Friedrich Wöhler and Antoine Bussy in 1828 by reacting beryllium compounds with potassium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] In 1910, radium was isolated as a pure metal by Curie and André-Louis Debierne also by electrolysis.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryl, a mineral that contains beryllium, has been known since the time of the Ptolemaic Kingdom in Egypt.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Although it was originally thought that beryl was an aluminum silicate, beryl was later found to contain a then-unknown element when, in 1797, Louis-Nicolas Vauquelin dissolved aluminum hydroxide from beryl in an alkali.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] In 1828, Friedrich Wöhler and Antoine Bussy independently isolated this new element, beryllium, by the same method, which involved a reaction of beryllium chloride with metallic potassium; this reaction was not able to produce large ingots of beryllium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] It was not until 1898, when Paul Lebeau performed an electrolysis of a mixture of beryllium fluoride and sodium fluoride, that large pure samples of beryllium were produced.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium was first produced by Humphry Davy in England in 1808 using electrolysis of a mixture of magnesia and mercuric oxide.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Antoine Bussy prepared it in coherent form in 1831.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Davy's first suggestion for a name was magnium, but the name magnesium is now used.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Lime has been used as a material for building since 7000 to 14,000 BCE, and kilns used for lime have been dated to 2,500 BCE in Khafaja, Mesopotamia.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium as a material has been known since at least the first century, as the ancient Romans were known to have used calcium oxide by preparing it from lime.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium sulfate has been known to be able to set broken bones since the tenth century.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium itself, however, was not isolated until 1808, when Humphry Davy, in England, used electrolysis on a mixture of lime and mercuric oxide, after hearing that Jöns Jakob Berzelius had prepared a calcium amalgam from the electrolysis of lime in mercury.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] In 1790, physician Adair Crawford discovered ores with distinctive properties, which were named *strontites* in 1793 by Thomas Charles Hope, a chemistry professor at the University of Glasgow, who confirmed Crawford's discovery.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium was eventually isolated in 1808 by Humphry Davy by electrolysis of a mixture of strontium chloride and mercuric oxide.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The discovery was announced by Davy on 30 June 1808 at a lecture to the Royal Society.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Barite, a mineral containing barium, was first recognized as containing a new element in 1774 by Carl Scheele, although he was able to isolate only barium oxide.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Barium oxide was isolated again two years later by Johan Gottlieb Gahn.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Later in the 18th century, William Withering noticed a heavy mineral in the Cumberland lead mines, which are now known to contain barium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Barium itself was finally isolated in 1808 when Humphry Davy used electrolysis with molten salts, and Davy named the element *barium*, after baryta.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Later, Robert Bunsen and Augustus Matthiessen isolated pure barium by electrolysis of a mixture of barium chloride and ammonium chloride.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] While studying uraninite, on 21 December 1898, Marie and Pierre Curie discovered that, even after uranium had decayed, the material created was still radioactive.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The material behaved somewhat similarly to barium compounds, although some properties, such as the color of the flame test and spectral lines, were much different.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] They announced the discovery of a new element on 26 December 1898 to the French Academy of Sciences.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Radium was named in 1899 from the word *radius*, meaning *ray*, as radium emitted power in the form of rays.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium occurs in the Earth's crust at a concentration of two to six parts per million (ppm), much of which is in soils, where it has a concentration of six ppm.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium is one of the rarest elements in seawater, even rarer than elements such as scandium, with a concentration of 0.2 parts per trillion.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] However, in freshwater, beryllium is somewhat more common, with a concentration of 0.1 parts per billion.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium and calcium are very common in the Earth's crust, being respectively the fifth and eighth most abundant elements.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] None of the alkaline earth metals are found in their elemental state.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Common magnesium-containing minerals are carnallite, magnesite, and dolomite.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Common calcium-containing minerals are chalk, limestone, gypsum, and anhydrite.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium is the 15th most abundant element in the Earth's crust.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The principal minerals are celestite and strontianite.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Barium is slightly less common, much of it in the mineral barite.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Radium, being a decay product of uranium, is found in all uranium-bearing ores.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Due to its relatively short half-life, radium from the Earth's early history has decayed, and present-day samples have all come from the much slower decay of uranium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Production of the six alkaline earth metals can occur in many ways.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Most beryllium is extracted from beryllium hydroxide.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] One production method is sintering, done by mixing beryl, sodium fluorosilicate, and soda at high temperatures to form sodium fluoroberyllate, aluminum oxide, and silicon dioxide.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] A solution of sodium fluoroberyllate and sodium hydroxide in water is then used to form beryllium hydroxide by precipitation.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Alternatively, in the melt method, powdered beryl is heated to high temperature, cooled with water, then heated again slightly in sulfuric acid, eventually yielding beryllium hydroxide.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The beryllium hydroxide from either method then produces beryllium fluoride and beryllium chloride through a somewhat long process.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Electrolysis or heating of these compounds can then produce beryllium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] In general, strontium carbonate is extracted from the mineral celestite through two methods: by leaching the celestite with sodium carbonate, or in a more complicated way involving coal.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] To produce barium, barite (impure barium sulfate) is converted to barium sulfide by carbothermic reduction (such as with coke).
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The sulfide is water-soluble and easily reacted to form pure barium sulfate, used for commercial pigments, or other compounds, such as barium nitrate.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] These in turn are calcined into barium oxide, which eventually yields pure barium after reduction with aluminum.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The most important supplier of barium is China, which produces more than 50% of world supply.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium is usually produced from magnesite ore, as well as dolomite.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] When dolomite is crushed, roasted and mixed with seawater in large tanks, magnesium hydroxide settles to the bottom.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Heating, mixing in coke, and reacting with chlorine, then produces molten magnesium chloride.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] This can be electrolyzed, releasing magnesium, which floats to the surface.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium is the fifth most abundant element in the Earth's crust, existing mostly as calcium carbonate.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Other important minerals of calcium include gypsum, anhydrite, fluorite, and apatite.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The largest producers of calcium in the world are China and Russia, where Davy's method of electrolysis is used on calcium chloride to produce the metal.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Other large producers of calcium are the U.S. and Canada, where lime is reduced with aluminium at high temperatures.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Marie Skłodowska-Curie developed the first methods of radium extraction using residues of pitchblende, following her extraction of uranium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] These residues contained mostly barium sulfate.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Curie's method was used until 1940, after which mixed bromides became more popular.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] As of 2011, radium is extracted only from spent reactor fuel as oxides.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] The pure metal can be isolated by reduction with aluminium in a vacuum at 1,200 °C.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium is used mainly in military applications, but non-military uses exist.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] In electronics, beryllium is used as a p-type dopant in some semiconductors, and beryllium oxide is used as a high-strength electrical insulator and heat conductor.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium alloys are used for mechanical parts when stiffness, light weight, and dimensional stability are required over a wide temperature range.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Beryllium-9 is used in small-scale neutron sources that use the reaction 9Be + 4He (α) → 12C + 1n, the reaction used by James Chadwick when he discovered the neutron.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Its low atomic weight and low neutron absorption cross-section would make beryllium suitable as a neutron moderator, but its high price and the readily available alternatives such as water, heavy water and nuclear graphite have limited this to niche applications.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] In the FLiBe eutectic used in molten salt reactors, beryllium's role as a moderator is more incidental than the desired property leading to its use.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] It offers advantages over other structural materials such as aluminum, but magnesium's usage is hindered by its flammability.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium is often alloyed with aluminum, zinc and manganese to increase its strength and corrosion resistance.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Magnesium has many other industrial applications, such as its role in the production of iron and steel, and in the Kroll process for production of titanium.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium is used as a reducing agent in the separation of other metals such as uranium from ore.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] It is a major component of many alloys, especially aluminum and copper alloys, and is also used to deoxidize alloys.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Calcium has roles in the making of cheese, mortars, and cement.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium and barium have fewer applications than the lighter alkaline earth metals.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Strontium carbonate is used in the manufacturing of red fireworks.
[src:condensed-aerosol-fire-suppression/alkaline-earth-metal] Pure strontium is used in the study of neurotransmitter release in neurons.
